<FIRST>r a AM-GeneralSentenced     08-07 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-General Sentenced,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Army General Gets Probation In Fraud Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A retired Army brigadier general was
given two years probation Monday on his conviction for conspiracy
to defraud the federal government.
   George H. Young Jr., 68, of Leavenworth, Kan., pleaded guilty in
June to the count stemming from an investigation of him and his
defense consulting company, the Milton Corp.
   Young retired from the Army in 1971 after being censured for
failure to adequately investigate the massacre of South Vietnamese
civilians by American troops at My Lai in 1968.
   The indictment, returned in Michigan, accused Young and the
company of sending periodic monthly payments between 1984 and 1986
to Army Capt. James McDowell of the Army Tank Automotive Command in
Warren, Mich., ``in return for procurement information regarding
government defense contracts.''
   McDowell told his superiors about contacts with Young and
cooperated with federal investigators.
   Ottawa Truck, a company from Ottawa, Kan., that was working on
development of an all-terrain supply vehicle, was a client of
Young's company. Ottawa Truck was not charged in the case, but was
named an unindicted co-conspirator.
   Under a plea agreement with the U.S. attorney's office in
Detroit, which prosecuted the case, a bribery charge to which Young
pleaded innocent was dismissed at sentencing.
   U.S. District Judge Earl O'Connor ordered a three-year prison
term for Young, but suspended the sentence and placed him on two
years probation. A condition of probation requires Young to do up
to 300 hours of community service work.
   The case had been transferred to Kansas for the plea and
sentencing because of Young's ailing health.
</TEXT>
