<FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-89 0117EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-Hostages     08-07 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Hostages,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mitchell: Moderation by Iranian President May Weaken Influence Over
Terrorists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell says a
shift away from ``Islamic fanaticism'' by the new president of Iran
is welcome, but it may also weaken his influence over terrorists
holding Americans hostage in Lebanon.
   Mitchell also said Sunday that, ``Ultimately, the hosage crisis
will not be solved until the Lebanon crisis is solved.''
   The Maine Democrat, interviewed on ABC's ``This Week with David
Brinkley,'' called for pressuring Syria to stop letting terrorists
operate with impunity in Lebanon.
   The White House offered no comment Sunday on the reported offer
by captors of American Joseph Cicippio to free him in exchange for
a Shiite Moslem cleric and several hundred Shiite and Palestinian
prisoners held by the Israelis.
   Bill Harlow, a White House spokesman, said, ``We wouldn't
comment on it in any way ... We try not to react to each individual
rumor or report. It's a very fluid situation and that doesn't do
any good.''
   ``The diplomatic efforts continue,'' said Harlow.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III, in Mexico City for a
conference of U.S. and Mexican Cabinet members, was asked about the
demands for Cicippio's release and said, ``our well-established
policy is not to negotiate with terrorists.
   ``If the United States were to get into that game, we'd simply
see a lot more Americans taken hostage around the world,'' Baker
said.
   Mitchell said that with the death of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini
and the election of Hashemi Rafsanjani as Iran's new president,
``there is a movement within Iran away from Islamic fanaticism and
more an attempt toward moderation.''
   ``That's a welcome development from our standpoint,'' Mitchell
said. But it may also reduce ``their direct control over these
groups ... No one can say for sure that each and every order by
Rafsanjani will be followed precisely by the Hezbollah.''
   Moshe Arens, the foreign minister of Israel, predicted on ABC
that if Israel and United States keep talking and acting tough to
terrorists and the states that back them, ``we may not see many
more abductions in the Middle East.''
   Hussein Mousawi, a leader of the pro-Iranian Hezbollah, told
reporters Sunday in Lebanon that his group may kill an Israeli
prisoner unless Israel returns Sheik Abdul Karim Obeid.
   Israel has offered to swap Obeid and 150 Shiite prisoners for
all Western hostages and three Israeli soldiers held in Lebanon.
Israeli commandos abducted Obeid on July 28; three days later a
group called the Organization for the Oppressed on Earth claimed to
have executed Marine Lt. Col. William Higgins in revenge.
   Arens said Obeid was ``of some importance amongst those band of
criminals ... We seem to be holding an important card which may
make it possible ... to release all of the hostages.'' But he
cautioned against expecting an early release.
   Yitzhak Rabin, Israel's defense minister, said on CBS' ``Face
the Nation'' that ``we will not separate anything'' in the proposed
exchange of hostages, but the Israeli soldiers are ``our first
priority.''
   Rabin said he felt more responsibility for his three captured
soldiers than Cicippio, ``an American that converted to Islam and
decided to stay in Lebanon.''
   Sen. William S. Cohen, R-Maine, a key member of the Senate
Intelligence Committee, said on NBC's ``Meet the Press'' that Bush
was ``doing the correct thing ... pursuing every conceivable
diplomatic initiative.''
   However, Cohen said, ``Patience in the face of prolonged
savagery really is not patience at all, but it's a policy of
appeasement.'' He urged the West to form a united front against
states that back the terrorists.
   Former U.S. Secretary of State Henry Kissinger said on ABC that,
``We have to devalue the hostages'' and convince the terrorists
``that the United States will not let itself get jerked around
every year or every six months by threats of murder.''
</TEXT>
