<FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-89 0120EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Congress     08-07 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressional Democrats Seeking Political Agenda</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic-controlled Congress is on
summer vacation, having calmed its internal strife but still
searching for a political agenda to steal thunder from a popular
president.
   With the scandal and resignation of House Speaker Jim Wright two
months behind them, Democrats feel ``very positive. I think we're
back on top. We feel we're in control,'' said Rep. Mike Synar,
D-Okla.
   Democrats cite a rush of spending bills and other routine
legislation in the past few weeks as evidence of effective
leadership from Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine,
and especially Speaker Thomas S. Foley, who took over when Wright
resigned.
   ``I must say that since Tom Foley came on, things have fallen
into place around here in a remarkable sort of way,'' concedes Rep.
Robert Michel of Illinois, the Republican leader.
   But the Democrats haven't found victory on the kinds of issues
they hoped would help define their party and chip away at the GOP
lock on the White House. The president has proved to be an elusive
target.
   ``I think the real difficulty is drawing a line or delineating
the difference between this administration and the Democratic
Congress,'' said Sen. James Sasser, D-Tenn., chairman of the Senate
Budget Committee.
   In the Senate, Democrats beat Bush's nomination of John Tower
for Secretary of Defense, and more recently the nomination of
William Lucas to head the Justice Department's civil rights
division. But those were hardly the ideological battles of the
former President Reagan's era.
   On minimum wage, Democrats could not override Bush's veto. They
then failed to paint him as being mean-spirited on the issue,
because unlike Reagan, Bush's position wasn't extreme opposition
but simply supporting a smaller increase than the Democrats
preferred.
   The House Democratic leadership attempted to make a class issue
of Bush's support of a capital gains tax cut, but conservatives in
their own party have sided with the White House.
   Politically murkier still for the leadership was Bush's threat
last week to veto his huge savings and loan bailout plan if it
contained a Democratic plan for financing the scheme. Bush won
concessions, as Democrats couldn't muster veto-override strength.
   The House has shredded Bush's defense budget and voted to ease
abortion spending rules for the District of Columbia. But new veto
threats could reverse those outcomes.
   Michael Robinson, a professor of government at Georgetown
University, said Bush is adept at handling Congress but also ``the
most acquiescent toward Congress since Eisenhower or even before,''
he said.
   ``I like to call him the `Mr. Rogers' president,'' Robinson
said, referring to the children's television program. Congress is a
neighborhood where he is comfortable, and he doesn't want to tackle
issues that make enemies.
   ``We're going to work on the margins for the next several years
... environment, campaign reform, welfare policy. It's going to be
a time of tinkering,'' Robinson said. ``The press is going to find
this particularly boring to the point of loathsome.''
   Democrats who control the two chambers of Congress personally
like Bush, and although wary of some of the political operatives
Bush employs, they talk about an era of bipartisan cooperation on
legislation on clean air and child care.
   ``If the country does well, I think the Democrats will do
well,'' says Majority Leader Mitchell, citing progress on his
Senate legislative agenda.
   But some Democrats hope to find a popular message, a theme, for
the party to campaign on nationally.
   ``There's a lot of soul-searching going on, and a lot of deep
thinking as to just what should be the honed-down Democratic
agenda,'' Sasser said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
