<FIRST>r a PM-RiotAnniversary Bjt   08-07 0768</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Riot Anniversary, Bjt,0789</SECOND>
<HEAD>New York Park Battle Pits Homeless, Anarchists and Yuppies</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY13</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAUL REYES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tompkins Square Park has the features of any of
the small patches of green in New York's dense inner city: Children
laugh on swings, old men play cards, couples snuggle on benches.
   But recently it has become less an oasis than the front line in
an ugly battle over one of the city's most diverse neighborhoods.
   A year ago, on the night of Aug. 6-7, the park in the heart of
the East Village was bloodied by a four-hour clash between
demonstrators and police that left 52 people injured and led to the
filing of more than 110 claims of police brutality.
   Police on Sunday arrested six people on disorderly conduct
charges at the end of a rally by about 100 people observing the
riot's first anniversary.
   The park remains a war zone, although the nature of the conflict
is in dispute. Is it a struggle by the homeless for a place to
live? Or a neighborhood's battle for control of its park?
   The melee last year began when police decided to enforce a 1
a.m. curfew in the park, which some residents said had become a
noisy center for drug use.
   Although no one disputes that drugs are used in Tompkins Square
and other parks, activists _ many of them self-proclaimed
anarchists _ saw the police action as part of a wider move to
sanitize the neighborhood, making it safe for yuppies and too
expensive for many others.
   As many as 250 people sleep in the park on any given night, most
of them homeless. But a few are activists with the political agenda
of demonstrating the inadequacies of the city's housing policies.
   Mayor Edward I. Koch has said he wants to rehabilitate thousands
of abandoned apartments in the neighborhood, half at subsidized
rates for poor people and half at market prices to pay for the
subsidy.
   ``We don't want to keep an area in permanent poverty, which is,
I think, what the anarchists would like,'' he said last year.
   Many longtime residents are opposed to the actions of the more
radical activists, including the construction of a tent city in the
park and the holding of frequent marches and rallies.
   ``I have never seen such a mess like this,'' said A. ``Ziggy''
Skrnyk, a longtime resident. ``Today this is a jungle, a real
jungle.''
   The East Village, part of lower Manhattan called the Lower East
Side, has seen wave upon wave of immigrants and is currently home
to Hispanics and Eastern Europeans, as well as drug dealers and
users, artists, and punks, among others.
   Many abandoned buildings have been illegally occupied _ some by
addicts who squat in the bare premises to use drugs, others by
urban pioneers willing to make major repairs to escape high rents
elsewhere in the city.
   Over the years, the grubby chic of the area has attracted
wealthier tenants, leading to rent hikes. Activists feel the
police, responding to the complaints of these tenants, are the
enforcement arm of a city administration bent on transforming the
neighborhood by removing undesirables.
   Police have been careful since last year's riot, rarely
enforcing curfew in the park and avoiding violence when they remove
tents or make arrests. More than 11,000 city police officers have
been retrained in crowd control.
   On July 5, police tore down a tent city and evicted more than
130 people. They were greeted by a volley of bottles, eggs and
sticks, but did not retaliate. Last week, police removed eight
tents, over the protests of more than 70 people. Three were
arrested.
   ``You won't see excessive violence on the part of police
officers,'' said Deputy Inspector Michael Julian, commanding
officer of the Ninth Precinct.
   The Rev. Frank Scanlan of St. Brigid's Catholic Church agreed
that police had become ``very sensitive,'' but said they were prone
to massive displays of manpower.
   When the city evicted squatters from two abandoned buildings
last spring, police blocked access to several blocks around the
park, including doorways and his church's parking lot.
   ``I, a priest, had to ask permission to go into my parking
lot,'' Scanlan said.
   Many residents believe anarchists and Marxists could help ease
tensions by leaving.
   ``I think that some people in the park would want nothing more
than another big confrontation,'' said Kate Walter, a founder of
the St. Marks Place Block Association. ``Some of them are white,
middle-class people with homes who come here to rabble-rouse while
the homeless sit around with a bottle.''
</TEXT>
