<FIRST>r w PM-Congress-Abortion     08-07 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-Abortion,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Abortion Vote Indicates New Pressure on Lawmakers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Last week's surprise House vote against
restrictions on abortion funding doesn't mean the chamber now backs
abortion rights, but lawmakers say it does signal an awareness that
voters are watching.
   There is widespread agreement that following the Supreme Court's
July decision granting states more muscle to block abortions, the
issue has become extremely high-profile _ and fraught with
political consequences.
   ``People will be watching these votes very closely,'' said Rep.
Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz., who voted with the majority Wednesday to reject
a ban on public financing of all abortions in the District of
Columbia.
   ``It makes people wonder, `How will this be used in a 10-second
or 30-second commercial against me,''' Kolbe said.
   The House's 219-206 vote against the financing ban was a
surprise to both sides. It was a reversal of last year's 222-186
vote approving similar restrictions, and marked the first time
since 1980 that the House rejected an effort to restrict abortion.
   Twenty-three lawmakers switched from an anti-abortion vote in
1988 to a vote backing abortion rights vote last week, and several
gave varying reasons.
   The way the measure was crafted did not help. The proposal,
introduced by Rep. Robert Dornan, R-Calif., allowed no exceptions
to a ban on public aid for abortions, even if the mother's life
were endangered.
   Dornan said the exception for the mother's life was omitted only
for procedural reasons, and conceded after the vote that the
omission cost him votes and was a tactical mistake. Not only did
Dornan lose, but those who supported him left themselves vulnerable
to opponents next year.
   ``They've got some of their colleagues hung out on a record vote
to deny money for abortions even when the life of the mother is at
risk,'' said Rep. Les AuCoin, D-Ore., one of the House's prime
pro-choice advocates. ``If they don't think the Democratic Party or
pro-choice groups will run political commercials on that, they're
living in dreamland.''
   AuCoin's prediction reflects a change in momentum on the
abortion issue, attributable to the Supreme Court decision, Webster
vs. Reproductive Health Services. Advocates of abortion rights say
their supporters have been galvanized by that ruling, and their
opponents concede that things are different _ for now.
   ``Some members, particularly some Democrats, have been hearing
quite a lot of noise from the other side recently and went to the
floor a little more disposed to listen to the other side,'' Douglas
Johnson, lobbyist for the National Right to Life Committee, said
last week.
   ``I don't think it means in most cases that they're permanently
shifting to the other column,'' he said. ``It does mean we need to
sit down with them again.''
   Even most lawmakers who back abortion rights agree that most
House members will continue to support abortion restrictions.
   ``We don't suddenly have a surprise pro-choice majority here,''
AuCoin conceded.
   Anti-abortion legislators said they faced another problem during
the Wednesday vote: dishonest lobbying by the abortion rights bloc.
Dornan and his supporters accused AuCoin and his allies of
misleading lawmakers by telling them Dornan's proposal would have
ended public aid in the district for contraceptives, which they say
is not true.
   Of several lawmakers who changed their votes from anti-abortion
in 1988 to the pro-choice side last week, the explanations varied.
   Kolbe describes himself as backing the right to abortion but an
opponent of using federal money for abortions. He said he ``fell
off the wagon'' last year, but now believes Congress should not
impose its will on the district government.
   Rep. Jim Slattery, D-Kan., said he was swayed by Dornan's
failure to exempt abortions involving endangered mothers, and a
fear that contraceptive aid would end.
   ``I couldn't vote against providing money for all abortions,''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
