<FIRST>r a PM-Contras-Calero     08-07 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Contras-Calero,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Calero Doesn't Expect Free Elections; Won't Ask Contras to Disband</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Central America</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contra leader Adolfo Calero said he won't
ask the guerrilla group to disband before the February elections in
Nicaragua, which he said he did not expect to be free despite a
pledge by the Sandinistas.
   ``We are ready to exchange our weapons for democracy,'' said
Calero, a leader of the Contra directorate, ``but we are not ready
to exchange weapons for promises.''
   Calero spoke Saturday to the annual convention of the Civilian
Materiel Assistance, a group based in Decatur, Ala., that has
furnished supplies to the Contras since 1983.
   Five Central American presidents at a summit meeting Sunday
failed to agree on a timetable for their earlier agreement that the
Nicaraguan rebels be dismantled.
   Calero said he is prepared to return to Nicaragua to be a
candidate in the elections, but said the Contras will ``remain in
the hills'' regardless of what President Daniel Ortega or the U.S.
government decide.
   The Bush administration has said it wants to have the Contras,
most of whom are based in Honduras, remain intact until the
elections.
   Civilian Materiel Assistance's chairman, Tom Posey, was indicted
with five other men for violating the U.S. Neutrality Act in 1984
and 1985. The charges were dismissed July 13 by a Miami judge who
noted that the U.S. government was waging an illegal war, organized
by national security official Oliver North, at the time.
   Calero said Posey's group ``made a great difference'' because it
provided American support at times when Congress refused to provide
aid.
   ``The CMA people believe freedom just doesn't happen,'' said
Calero.
