<FIRST>u i PM-SriLanka-Maldives     08-07 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka-Maldives,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Death Sentence for Six in Maldives Coup Attempt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six Sri Lankans convicted of
participating in an attempted coup in the Maldives last year have
been sentenced to death, a Maldivian official said today.
   Mohammed Ahmed, a Maldivian Foreign Ministry official, said the
sentences were ordered Sunday by the high court in Male, capital of
the Maldives.
   Sources in Male who spoke on condition of anonymity said Chief
Justice Moosa Fathy read the sentences at a public hearing after
nearly two months of trial. No dates were set for the executions,
they said.
   Ahmed said there was no higher court of appeal and that only
President Maumoon Abdul Gayoom could commute the sentences.
   The last death sentence carried out in the Maldives was in 1953,
he said when contacted by telephone from New Delhi.
   The Maldives, a string of coral islands in the Indian Ocean, are
about 500 miles southwest of Sri Lanka and roughly the same
distance south of India.
   Eight other Sri Lankans were sentenced to jail terms, Ahmed
said. He said he did not know the exact terms.
   A total of 68 Sri Lankans and seven Maldivians were arrested
after the Nov. 3 coup attempt, which was crushed by Indian
paratroopers responding to a call for help from Gayoom. At least 17
people, mosty local residents, were killed in the fighting.
   The Maldivian government has said the Sri Lankans were
mercenaries and belonged to a Sri Lankan guerrilla group, the
People's Liberation Organization of Tamil Eelam, which participated
in a Tamil separatist war against Sri Lanka's Sinhalese majority.
   Ahmed said the others accused were to appear in court later this
week for verdicts and sentencing.
   The coup was led by Abdullah Luthufi, a Sri Lanka-based
Maldivian. Ahmed said Luthufi has appeared in court but that no
decision has been made in his case.
</TEXT>
