<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     08-07 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises 1.73 Yen, Tokyo Shares Drop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose sharply Monday against the
Japanese yen in Tokyo while share prices on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange lost ground.
   The dollar closed at 139.78 yen, up 1.73 yen from last Friday's
closing of 138.05 yen. It opened the week's trading at 139.55 yen
and ranged between 139.10 and 139.80 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues lost 111.61
points, or 0.32 percent, to end trading at 34,630.38. The index
declined 37.82 points on Friday.
   Currency dealers attributed the dollar's jump to its upswing in
New York last Friday following an unexpected drop in the U.S.
jobless rate for July.
   ``There was some active buying of the dollar by players who are
relieved of the anxiety that the Fed will relax its interest rates
further,'' said a dealer at a major commercial bank, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   Washington last Friday announced the nation's unemployment rate
for July was 5.2 percent, down 0.1 percentage point from an earlier
month, reassuring market players that the U.S. economy was still
growing moderately.
   But the dollar is unlikely to keep rising ``because market
players tend to sell the U.S. currency for profit-taking whenever
it approaches the 140-yen mark,'' said a dealer at the Bank of
Japan, requesting anonymity.
   Securities dealers said the yen's weakness and political
uncertainties are depressing stock prices.
   ``Until the new government under a fresh prime minister gets
going, I don't expect a summer rally,'' said a dealer at Nikko
Securities Co., speaking anonymously.
   The governing Liberal Democratic Party is expected to chose a
new leader who will replace Prime Minister Sousuke Uno as Japan's
prime minister.
</TEXT>
