<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     08-07 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bride wore white but the theme was
definitely purple-and-gold when a couple recited their vows in
Louisiana State University's Tiger Stadium.
   Wendell Brumfield, 36, wed Margaret Norsworthy on the 50-yard
line while 20 relatives and friends watched from the Tiger bench
Saturday.
   ``I haven't missed an LSU home game in 10 years,'' Brumfield
said. ``So I couldn't think of a better place to get married.''
   Brumfield's obsession with the Bayou Bengals was a little lost
on Norsworthy, who had never been in the stadium before.
   ``This ought to make you a Tiger fan,'' said her father, Wallace
Norsworthy.
   ``It might. I've never even seen the place,'' she said.
   As Brumfield entered the stadium, he stared at the thousands of
empty purple and gold seats surrounding him.
   ``It's not like a Tiger game,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ELK RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A transplanted Dane is trying to
introduce Americans to a wide variety of mustards more typical of
his native Europe.
   Johan Bech uses mustard seed from the plains of Montana and
Saskatchewan in his Classic Sharp, Sweet 'n' Tangy and ``Gee John''
mustards, sold in markets in the Great Lakes region and through the
mail.
   ``The standard salad-type mustard doesn't offer much in taste,''
he said. ``As soon as we've had people taste ours, they are genuine
followers. It's like an addiction almost.''
   Bech, 51, and six employees use a water-cooled, Swiss-built
milling system that grinds the whole mustard seeds into the final
product. Using the whole seed makes a difference in taste and
consistency, Bech said.
   ``Our mustard shows that it has fantastic holding power in the
oven or on the grill,'' he said. ``You can take a basic mustard and
do many things with it.''
   He will introduce a new variety this fall that isn't for the
timid.
   The cherry nut honey mustard is ``hotter than hell _ I tell you,
it scared me,'' he said.
   Born in Randers, Denmark, Bech moved to Canada in 1961 to get
into the furniture business. He began his quest for ``the perfect
mustard'' years ago while in Canada, where he noticed a gap in the
North American mustard market.
</TEXT>
