<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     08-07 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up 1.73 Yen, Tokyo Stocks Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose sharply today against the
Japanese yen while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange fell in
slow trading, dealers said.
   The dollar closed at 139.78, up 1.73 yen from last Friday's
close of 138.05 yen. It opened the week's trading at 139.55 yen and
ranged between 139.10 yen and 139.80 yen.
   The dollar now has climbed 3.58 yen in the last three trading
days.
   A dealer at the Bank of Tokyo, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, attributed the dollar's jump today to its rise in New
York last Friday following an unexpected drop in the U.S. jobless
rate for July.
   The U.S. government announced last Friday that the nation's
unemployment rate for July was 5.2 percent, down 0.1 percentage
point from the previous month, reassuring market players that the
U.S. economy was still growing moderately, the dealer said.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, the market's
main barometer, fell by 111.61 points, or 0.32 percent, closing at
34,630.38. It had lost 37.82 points last Friday.
   Volume traded on the first session totaled 300 million shares,
compared with 350 million shares last Friday.
   An official at Nomura Securities Co., who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said the market was quiet as investors watched Japan's
political situation. The governing Liberal Democratic Party will
chose a new leader Tuesday to succeed Prime Minister Sousuke Uno.
The new leader is to be elected prime minister Wednesday by
Parliament.
</TEXT>
