<FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-89 0503EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonBriefs     08-07 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington Briefs,520</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spending for food is taking a smaller bite
from the household budget, continuing a general trend of recent
years, according to an Agriculture Department study.
   According to the department's food cost review, Americans
overall spent $411 billion on food in 1988 _ 11.8 percent of their
total disposable personal income. That's down from 13 percent five
years earlier and 13.5 percent in 1978.
   Citing a 1986 survey by the U.S. Department of Labor, the
Agriculture Department noted that the percentage of income spent on
food varies by size and income of family.
   After-tax income spent for food varied from 12.7 percent for
households with incomes of $30,000-$39,000, to 27.4 percent for
families with incomes of $5,000-$9,999.
   Although much has been said about the growing number of meals
taken at restaurants and fast-food establishments, the share of
disposable income on food eaten away from home has risen only
gradually: from 3.2 percent in 1929 to 4.5 percent in 1988.
Expense-account meals are excluded.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Urban League President John E. Jacob
has lashed out against the Supreme Court, saying the institution
that blacks once hoped would protect their interests has now become
``a threat to our rights.''
   Opening the league's annual conference Sunday, Jacob implored
the Congress and the Bush administration to lessen the impact of
recent high court rulings that he said were anti-civil rights.
   Unless these decisions are rolled back, Jacob said, women and
minorities ``won't be allowed to play catchup. They'll be stuck
with the effects of past discrimination.''
   Jacob cited recent court rulings: against contracts set aside
for minority businesses, preventing women and minorities from
challenging standing seniority systems, limiting the use of
statistics in proving patterns of discrimination and putting
greater burdens of proof on victims of discrimination.
   ``We call on the president and the Congress to carefully review
the court's anti-civil rights decisions and to frame corrective
legislation,'' he said in the keynote address.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Airlines are hiring record numbers of pilots,
according to figures supplied by the Air Line Pilots Association, a
labor union. The organization said that large and small carriers
have hired 12,000 pilots so far this year, compared to 9,800 for
all of last year.
   But not all of the new hires are new pilots. Many are moving up
an informal ladder to flying the most sophisticated commercial
jets, resulting in an exodus among military pilots and turnover of
up to 120 percent a year for small carriers. Flight schools also
are seeing more trainers leave to enter the cockpit, according to
the union, known by the acronym ALPA.
   ``The military and the regional airlines together continue to
supply a large share of the major airline pilot workforce, but they
cannot meet the present or future demand,'' said Henry A. Duffy,
president of the 41,000-member pilots union.
   Airline industry analysts estimate that between 40,000 and
60,000 new pilots will be needed over the next decade.
</TEXT>
