<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon-Target     08-07 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Target,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hovercraft Targeted by Syrian Artillery, Two Girls Dead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HASAN MROUE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LARNACA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The captain of a Norwegian hovercraft
that sails daily between Cyprus and Lebanon said Syrian gunners
tried to sink the vessel when they fired dozens of rockets into the
sea off the Lebanese Christian port of Jounieh.
   Two Lebanese sisters, aged 15 months and 2 years, drowned when a
boat ferrying 16 passengers out to the hovercraft capsized in the
waves churned up by the barrage before dawn Sunday.
   ``I believe we were the target. Firing 40 rockets isn't to scare
you. It's to hit you,'' Capt. Sundsford Asbjorn said in an
interview in the port of Larnaca.
   There was no immediate comment from Syrian forces, who have
besieged the enclave where 1 million Christians live for five
months. They shell the coastline daily to prevent supplies of
weapons, fuel and food from getting through.
   The siege started in March in retaliation for Gen. Michel Aoun's
blockade of illegal ports operated by Syrian-backed Moslem militias
south of Beirut. He was hoping to recover an estimated $100 million
lost annually in customs dues.
   The hovercraft service began in May after regular passenger
ferries decided it was too dangerous to continue sailing to
Jounieh. Under normal conditions it takes 3{ hours to make the
100-mile voyage.
   The blue-and-white hovercraft usually whirs into the dock at
Jounieh under cover of darkness.
   But when the Syrians started shelling it moved offshore and the
passengers were ferried out in small craft.
   At 2 a.m. Sunday the 320-seat Santa Maria headed out to sea to
avoid the shelling but turned back when the boat flipped over about
300 yards offshore.
   ``No matter what risks are involved, you must save people, so I
turned back and put on the lights ... and gave the crew permission
to jump into the sea,'' the bearded skipper said.
   Navigation officer Cesar Abi Aql, 25, swam back and forth to the
raft pulling people to safety but said he couldn't manage to save
the baby girls, 15-month-old Maya Azar and her sister Roba.
   ``I saw the baby girls but I had another passenger clinging to
me,'' he said. ``When I went back they'd disappeared.''
   The girls were later found and pronounced dead on arrival at the
hospital in Jounieh.
   Lebanese passenger Jack Nassar, 50, and his wife, Jumana, who
suffered a broken leg, said they struggled in choppy waters for 20
minutes. Their 10-year-old daughter Miryam and son Maroun, 7, were
among those taken back to Jounieh.
   ``I could hardly talk because I had swallowed a lot of water and
my leg was broken. ... My husband was weeping and screaming because
he thought they were dead,'' Mrs. Nassar said at Larnaca General
Hospital.
   The passengers' suitcases were left floating in the sea.
</TEXT>
