<FIRST>r a PM-FiresRdp     08-07 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fires Rdp,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weather Creates New Problems For Western Firefighters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Red warning flags went out for threatened ``dry lightning''
storms in Idaho, and winds whipped flames around a brush fire in
Utah as dozens of fires burned in seven western states.
   More than 900 lightning strikes were reported Sunday in eastern
Oregon, where firefighters had earlier managed to contain the worst
of a half-dozen major forest fires. Crews were sent to investigate
one new fire on the Ochoco National Forest as forecasters called
for more thunderstorms today.
   About 23,000 firefighters were battling blazes on 173,000 acres
in Idaho, California, Oregon, Utah, Nebraska, Montana and New
Mexico, according to the Boise Interagency Fire Center, the federal
wildfire command post.
   More than 220,000 acres have been scorched in a bout of
wildfires that began 1{ weeks ago.
   The worst fires were in Idaho, where 9,000 firefighters and army
troops battled 28 major fires and gathering thunderstorms
threatened to bring new blazes.
   Officials blame dry lightning storms that jolted the state a
little more than a week ago for sparking most of the fires.
Sunday's forecast was for a return of the same.
   ``We have a `red flag' warning on,'' said Laurel Simosam,
spokeswoman for the Boise center. ``Our forecast is for dry
thunderstorms and high winds.''
   Crews in the Payette National Forest were attacking fires that
had blackened 18,000 acres near the mining town of Warren, which
was not threatened for the moment.
   Forest supervisors were sending 400 firefighters to establish
lines on a 11,657-acre blaze close to fish habitat in the scenic
South Fork of the Salmon River.
   More than 120,000 acres of Idaho timber and rangeland have
burned in the recent fires; 31,800 acres were involved in
uncontrolled blazes Sunday, casting a pall over Boise, where the
mercury soared to 100.
   Before the lightning strikes, eastern Oregon firefighters had
consolidated gains made during cool weather last week and were
predicting that many of the 100 forest fires that have burned
82,000 acres would be contained by mid-week. A 10,900-acre blaze
raged next to the Hells Canyon Wilderness on the Oregon-Idaho
border, where rugged terrain slowed the work of cutting containment
lines, said Forest Service spokeswoman Dody Yaccarino.
   California firefighters gained ground Sunday against a stubborn
15,100-acre wildfire in Cleveland National Forest and a 7,000-acre
blaze in the Sierra Nevada foothills.
   In Utah, erratic winds pushed flames past control lines around a
1,700-acre brush fire consuming sagebrush, grass and pine trees in
steep terrain about 30 miles east of Salt Lake City.
   The winds helped the Chalk Creek fire grow 500 acres on Sunday,
but authorities said it did not pose a threat to oil fields in the
area.
   A firefighter was critically injured when a tree feel on him
during a successful battle by 500 crew members to contain the
3,000-acre Pryor Gap blaze on the Crow Indian Reservation.
   In Nebraska, a fire that blackened 3,000 acres of brush and
timber in canyon country near Belmont in the state's northwest
corner was largely contained Sunday, but control wasn't expected
for two to three days.
   Civil defense coordinator Tom Brown said the fire may have been
started by sparks from a passing train.
   More than 100 firefighters were engaged battling a single
800-acre fire in New Mexico, according to the Boise fire center.
</TEXT>
