<HEAD>Dollar Firms in London, Gold Drops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar firmed in early European trading
today, following through on Friday's sharp gains. Gold prices fell.
   Foreign currency dealers said the market was thin, but that the
continuing uncertainty over the fate of western hostages in Lebanon
was giving the dollar some support.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 1.73 yen to a closing 139.78. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 140.25 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Monday:
   _1.9143 West German marks, up from 1.8975
   _1.6520 Swiss francs, up from 1.6353
   _6.4800 French francs, up from 6.4260
   _2.1573 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1300
   _1,377.50 Italian lire, up from 1,366.00
   _1.1770 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1775
   The dollar gained against the pound in London. It cost $1.5980
to buy one pound, compared with $1.6150 late Friday.
   Gold opened in London at $367.75 a troy ounce, compared with
late Friday's $370.75. At midmorning, the city's five major bullion
dealers fixed a recommended price of $367.25.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $367.30, down from $370.50 late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 86 cents to close at $368.46.
   Silver was quoted in London at $5.16 a troy ounce, down from
Friday's $5.23.
