<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Weather     08-07 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Weather,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Typhoon, Earthquake Hit Japan; Eight Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tropical Storm Mac swept across northern Japan
during the night, triggering floods and landslides that killed
eight people and left seven others missing, police said today.
   The storm hit Fukushima Prefecture on Sunday. Today, an
earthquake measuring 5.6 on the Richter scale hit Hokkaido, but
there were no immediate reports of damage or injuries.
   The earthquake was centered in the ocean near Kushiro, in the
eastern part of Hokkaido island about 530 miles northeast of Tokyo,
according to the Central Meteorological Agency. It said there was
no danger of a tsunami, the dangerous wave sometimes caused by
earthquakes.
   Six people died Sunday when a 98-foot-long bridge collapsed in a
flooded river and three cars carrying a total of 11 people plunged
into the muddy stream, said an official with the Fukushima
Prefectural police who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   He said the other five still were missing.
   ``Water is all over the place, and we can no longer tell where
the river used to flow,'' said another police official.
   A 23-year-old man died when he fell into a flood-swollen river
elsewhere in Fukushima and a 53-year-old housewife was buried by a
landslide, the first official added.
   He said a 52-year-old man disappeared while helping firefighters
repair the banks of a river in Fukushima, and a seventh person was
missing in Miyagi prefecture just north of Fukushima.
   The storm also left 15 people injured, including 11 in
Fukushima, about 150 miles northeast of Tokyo, he said.
   He said 12 houses were destroyed, 4,042 houses were flooded,
roads were destroyed at 88 places, bridges were damaged at 21 and
landslides occurred at 108 places.
   The storm, listed as typhoon No. 13 as it approached Japan, had
weakened to a tropical storm by the time it hit Choshi, in Chiba,
with winds of 68 mph Sunday afternoon.
   The storm was off Japan's northernmost main island of Hokkaido
tonight, the Meteorological Agency said.
</TEXT>
