<FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-89 0741EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     08-07 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Killed in Overnight Shelling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FAROUK NASSAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian and Christian forces fought
nightlong duels with artillery and tank fire across the capital's
dividing Green Line, and five people were killed, police said today.
   Two of the overnight fatalities were in Christian east Beirut
and three in the Moslem west side, said a police spokesman who
cannot be named under standing rules. He said 16 people were
wounded.
   It was the 12th straight night of random bombardment that has
forced more than one million of Beirut's 1.5 million inhabitants to
flee to safer areas in Lebanon or abroad.
   The latest casualties raised the overall total to 547 killed and
1,300 wounded since the latest round in Lebanon's 14-year-old civil
war erupted March 8.
   The captain of a Norwegian hovercraft that sails daily from
Cyprus to Lebanon said Syrian gunners Sunday tried to sink his
vessel by firing 40 rockets into the sea off the Christian port of
Jounieh.
   Two Lebanese sisters, aged 15 months and 2 years, drowned when a
boat ferrying 16 passengers to the hovercraft capsized in waves
churned up by the Syrian barrage.
   Syrian gunners bombard the enclave's coastline daily in order to
prevent supplies of weapons and fuel reaching the Christians.
   The latest round in Lebanon's 14-year civil war erupted in
March, when Christian army commander Gen. Michel Aoun blockaded
illegal ports operated by Syrian-backed Moslem militias south of
Beirut that deny the state treasury of aorund $100 million a year
in lost customs dues.
   The Syrians joined their militia allies in shelling the
Christian enclave and also blocked its land exits.
   Police said the Syrian army on Saturday brought dozens of T-62
tanks and BM-21 multi-rocket launchers that can fire 40 rockets a
minute into west Beirut and the hills overlooking the capital.
   The reinforcements arrived amid rumors that Aoun's 20,000 troops
might storm west Beirut to seize Lebanon's central bank, where most
of the nation's hard currency and gold reserves are stored.
   Around 40,000 Syrian troops have been stationed in Lebanon since
1976 under a peacekeeping mandate from the Arab League.
   But Aoun charges the Syrians lost their credibility as
peacekeepers by siding with the Moslems in their fight for an equal
share of power with the traditionally dominant Christians.
   The 54-year-old Maronite Catholic general has vowed a ``war of
liberation'' to drive the Syrians out.
   King Fahd of Saudi Arabia, King Hassan II of Morocco and
Algerian President Chedli Bendjedid agreed at an Arab summit
conference at Casablanca, Morocco in May to mediate for a
settlement of the civil war.
   Their foreign ministers shuttled between Beirut and Damascus for
two months with a mandate to arrange a peace settlement by
November, but announced two weeks ago that the peacemaking efforts
had reached a ``dead end.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
