<FIRST>r a PM-AnotherLook:AtlantaTransit 1stLd-Writethru a0409 08-07
1021</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Another Look: Atlanta Transit, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0409,1036</SECOND>
<HEAD>After 10 Years, System Still Resisted in Some White Suburbs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to restore dropped `Atlanta' from agency's name.
Moved in advance Aug. 2 as b0180.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten years after gleaming silver trains started
rolling along the South's first rapid-transit system, a 1,582-mile
network of 150 bus routes and two rail lines with 29 stations
carries a quarter-million passengers a day.
   The Metropolitan Atlanta Rapid Transit Authority has been hailed
for its safety and cleanliness. MARTA celebrated its trains' 10th
birthday with a free-ride day on July 4 that drew a record 435,000
passengers. A revitalized Underground Atlanta draws up to 100,000
extra passengers a week, many of them first-time riders.
   But MARTA has a problem: It increasingly goes where much of
Atlanta isn't.
   When MARTA was launched in 1971, the three suburban counties
that refused it _ Cobb to the northwest, Gwinnett to the northeast
and Clayton to the south _ were largely rural, and it was hard to
imagine subway cars rolling past farms and forests. Those three
counties now hold nearly 900,000 people, three-fourths the number
in the two central counties, Fulton and DeKalb, where MARTA runs.
   Despite suburban traffic that is getting worse and suburban jobs
that go begging because car-less workers can't reach them,
opposition to expanding the system remains. Joining would almost
surely mean higher taxes, and suburban politicians have been loath
to submit to decision-makers in Atlanta.
   But the chief reason given by many opponents is the fear MARTA
will bring crime to their tranquil neighborhoods. That feeling is
widely seen as racism. MARTA's passengers reflect central Atlanta,
which is predominantly black.
   Atlantans may not like to discuss it, but few haven't heard the
acronym explained as: ``Moving Africans Rapidly Through Atlanta.''
   ``The people you hear opposing MARTA in Cobb and Gwinnett ...
they've been pretty open about it. They don't want black people
coming into their areas,'' said the Rev. Joseph Lowery, a civil
rights leader and a member of MARTA's board since 1975. ``It's
blind prejudice and fear.''
   ``We feel its in everyone's interest to have a regional transit
agency providing all the service,'' said General Manager Kenneth M.
Gregor. ``It makes sense, it's much more cost-effective,
unencumbered by the problems of numerous political jurisdictions. I
think that position ultimately will prevail.''
   ``I think MARTA's future is contingent on that,'' said Lowery.
``Its maximum potential will never be realized until we go north to
Cobb and Gwinnett and south to Clayton. ... We at least need five
counties.''
   End-of-the-line stops on MARTA's cross-shaped rail system do a
booming business as thousands of Cobb and Gwinnett residents drive
across the county line and hop on the train. Some luxury hotels in
Cobb have even sent vans to ferry workers across the Chattahoochee
River, which marks the county line.
   But MARTA trains and buses aren't going to cross that bridge
anytime soon.
   ``They're pretty much against it, at least in my end of the
county,'' said Gwinnett County Commissioner Curtis McGill. ``A
number of the people who have moved into the south end are
transplants from DeKalb County, and a lot of them feel like MARTA
ran them out of town.''
   ``Without being obvious, people say that ease of transportation
would bring in `the undesirables' and crime,'' said Gwinnett County
Commission Chairman Lillian Webb, who has advocated at least a
trial run of MARTA buses.
   Even talking about MARTA can be tricky in the suburbs. A
discussion group with Cobb County leaders in 1980 had a ``code name
so folks wouldn't know about it,'' Gregor said.
   But more and more, suburban Atlanta may be coming to the
conclusion that something must be done. A one-mile trip down a
major thoroughfare in Cobb or Gwinnett can take more than a
half-hour, and residents of those counties named traffic as their
No. 1 problem in a recent Atlanta Journal-Constitution poll.
   The poll found between 54 percent and 60 percent of Cobb,
Gwinnett and Clayton county residents favored MARTA trains in their
communities, although only in Cobb County were a majority willing
to pay the 1 percent sales tax that Fulton and DeKalb County
residents pay for MARTA.
   Meanwhile, Cobb County last month launched its own five-route
bus system. Ten thousand people used it the first week, more than
twice the volume expected for the first three weeks, forcing
officials to drop a radio advertising campaign for fear they
wouldn't be able to meet the demand.
   The busiest Cobb Community Transit route is one dropping
commuters at a midtown Atlanta MARTA subway station. Ultimately,
the service plans 10 routes, including three more Atlanta express
runs. Riders get free transfers to MARTA under a deal that allows
MARTA riders to hop on Cobb County's buses.
   The system, costing the county an estimated $2 million a year,
makes more sense than giving MARTA an estimated $65 million a year
in local sales taxes, said Craig Aronoff, chairman of the CCT
Advisory Board. ``It doesn't look like it would make sense to
provide more than we provide. ... MARTA's the best system in the
country, but it doesn't have all the answers.''
   ``In my judgment, they're fooling themselves,'' Gregor said.
``Ten bus routes aren't going to even dent, aren't going to put an
infinitesimal impact, on their traffic congestion. And starting a
bus system that brings four routes in the city of Atlanta ain't
going to do it.''
   Clayton County has no public transportation. Gwinnett, which has
none either, will vote next year on some sort of mass transit
referendum. Mrs. Webb hopes it will once and for all answer
questions like what the county wants and will pay for.
   ``I hope they'll use reason and understanding, rather than ...
illogical rationale,'' she said, pointing out that the county's
330,000 population will more than double in the next 20 years.
``The sheer mathematics of it says we have got to come up with some
method of handling all those people.
   ``It's inevitable. It's time to fish or cut bait.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
