<FIRST>r a PM-BlackCatholics 1stLd-Writethru a0489 08-07 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Black Catholics, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0489,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Catholics Defer Statement on Separate Rite</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, `Members of ...' to CORRECT meeting to July
27 sted last week and name of organization to National Black Catholic Clergy
Caucus.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black lay Catholics attending a three-day meeting
took no stand on whether to endorse a separate African-American
rite within the church.
   Leaders of the National Office for Black Catholics and the
National Black Lay Caucus said Sunday they would study written
comments collected at the conference before issuing a statement on
the rite.
   Members of the National Black Catholic Clergy Caucus,
representing priests and monks, endorsed at a meeting July 27 in
Milwaukee the study of such a rite, which would have its own
liturgy and its own hierarchy of priests and bishops.
   Black Catholics' questioning of their role in the American
church intensified last month when the Rev. George A. Stallings, a
Washington, D.C., priest, was suspended for forming a separate
black congregation over the objections of his archbishop, Cardinal
James A. Hickey.
   The executive director of the Office for Black Catholics, Walter
Hubbard, said he expects the tone of the statement to be
conciliatory.
   ``There must be some reconciliation,'' Hubbard said. ``There
must be some healing. I think Cardinal Hickey has been an
outstanding shepherd for his flock. But there's also a deep respect
for Father Stallings. We want to extend our hands to both of them.''
   Hubbard said black lay leaders have plans for an institute to
train lay members. He said a faculty and curriculum are being
formed but no site has been chosen.
   The need for greater lay involvement in the church was echoed
throughout the Atlanta conference, whose theme was ``Creating a
Spirit of African-American Leadership.''
   Plans for a National Day of Prayer for African-Americans on the
first Sunday in February were announced by the Rev. James Goode,
pastor of St. Paul of the Shipwreck Church in San Francisco.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
