<FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-89 0801EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Obit-DeKock     08-07 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-De Kock,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reserve Bank Governer Dies of Cancer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Another version appeared on financial wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reserve Bank Governor
Gerhardus de Kock, credited with bringing a market-oriented
approach to the country's monetary policy, died today of colon
cancer at the age of 63.
   De Kock headed a commission of inquiry into the monetary system
from 1977-82 which resulted in major changes, but not elimination,
of the practice of government intervention in the monetary system.
   In his last public address, in Durban early last month, De Kock
emphasized the need for the Reserve bank to have the freedom to
control monetary policy without any political interference. He said
there had been progress in the past year, but further steps were
required.
   He was due to have a farewell dinner on Friday after having
announced his plans to retire in October following eight years as
governor. His retirement was announced in June, but no mention was
made of his cancer.
   De Kock is to be succeeded by Chris Stals, special economics
adviser to the minister of finance and a former director-general of
the Department of Finance, but it was not announced whether he will
take over immediately or wait until November as planned.
   De Kock joined the Reserve Bank in 1956, becoming head of its
Economic Department in 1963.
   From 1968-71 he was an alternate director of the International
Monetary Fund in Washington, D.C., representing South Africa,
Australia, New Zealand, Lesotho and Swaziland. He returned to South
Africa when he was appointed one of three deputy governors of the
Reserve Bank.
   From 1977-82, De Kock chaired a commission of inquiry into South
Africa's monetary policy. The commission's recommendations on
changes in exchange rates, savings institutions, financial markets
and monetary policy were implemented by the government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
