<FIRST>r a PM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0480 08-07 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0480,0620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS deaths of Beuve-Mery and de Kock. PMs separates moved on
Mirdamadi as a0473; Beuve-Mery as a0498; de Kock as a0506, and Toran on
sports wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Hajieh Mirdamadi</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hajieh Mirdamadi, the mother of Iran's
new leader Ali Khamenei, died the day her son was confirmed as
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's successor, the Islamic Republic News
Agency reported today. She was 76.
   Ms. Mirdamadi, who lived in the provincial capital of Mashad,
died Sunday of heart failure, IRNA said.
   Iran's 83-man Assembly of Experts, the country's highest
spiritual authority, confirmed the 50-year-old Khamenei as leader
in a unanimous vote.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Stacey Toran</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stacey Toran, a starting strong safety with
the Los Angeles Raiders football team, was killed late Saturday
when his car went off a road near his home and overturned. He was
27.
   Born and raised in Indianapolis, Toran played at wide receiver
and defensive back at Broad Ripple High. In college, he starred at
Notre Dame as a cornerback and was defensive co-captain his senior
year.
   Toran was expected to be a major part of the Raiders' defense
this season. The 6-3, 200-pound Toran, a sixth-round draft choice
in 1984, was sidelined for most of last season after suffering a
sprained ankle and broken fibula. In 1987, he was considered one of
the team's best players.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Virginia Sims</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WICHITA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Virginia Sims, a leader of the Wichita
black community and former publisher of a weekly newspaper, died
Wednesday. She was 108.
   Mrs. Sims and her husband, the Rev. Hollie T. Sims, settled in
Wichita in 1919. They printed The Negro Star in a barn behind their
home for 30 years until Hollie Sims' death in 1953.
   Mrs. Sims is survived by her son, one grandchild, nine
great-grandchildren and 20 great-great grandchildren.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Hubert Beuve-Mery</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
