<FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-89 0840EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--McAuliffe-Flag 1stLd-Writethru a041stoppageaffectsoperationswithdatCharlestonCeremony
08-07 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--McAuliffe-Flag, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0415,0177</SECOND>
<HEAD>McAuliffe Flag Displayed at Charleston Ceremony</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT date of Challenger disaster to Jan.
28 sted Jan. 26.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A flag carried by teacher-astronaut
Christa McAuliffe aboard the Challenger will tour the United States
in her memory.
   It was one of 50 identical flags she carried aboard the space
shuttle, which blew up after takeoff on Jan. 28, 1986, killing
McAuliffe and the six other astronauts aboard.
   None of the other flags was salvaged from the wreckage.
   McAuliffe had planned to present the flags to the 50 states as
symbols of learning and liberty, said Board of Education spokesman
Carolyn Spangler. Instead, the display of the salvaged flag will
later tour the other 49 states.
   The 5-by-4 inch flag with a wave-like red, white and blue
pattern, was unveiled before a crowd of 1,600 Sunday at the
Charleston Civic Center. It was mounted on a seven-foot granite
display topped by a bronze sculpture of the hands of three children
holding up a flag.
</TEXT>
