<FIRST>r a PM-SpaceShuttle 1stLd-Writethru a0447 08-07 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Space Shuttle, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0447,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hush-Hush Countdown Continues for Tuesday Space Shuttle Launch</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE on weather outlook improving, astronauts
briefed, little catchup to do; PICKS UP 9th graf pvs, `Commanding the ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The weather outlook improved greatly
today as a blacked-out countdown advanced toward a Tuesday launch
of space shuttle Columbia on a mission to put a spy satellite into
orbit.
   The mission will be Columbia's first flight in 3{ years, during
which NASA's oldest shuttle was used for spare parts.
   Forecasters said there was only a 5 percent chance of
unfavorable weather interfering with the launch. That was down from
Sunday's prediction of 20 percent to 40 percent, based on the
possibility of clouds lingering in the area.
   ``It's looking very good,'' said Capt. Ken Warren, an Air Force
spokesman.
   The five astronauts received briefings on launch preparations as
sources reported the countdown today entered a planned 17-hour
hold, a period reserved for catching up on any lagging work. The
sources reported there was little catchup to do.
   Because the mission is classified, the Pentagon will permit NASA
to say only that liftoff will occur between 7:30 a.m. and 11:30
a.m. Tuesday.
   The space agency will make the countdown public just nine
minutes before launch and will provide only three brief
announcements during the five-day mission on the spacecraft's
condition and on the landing time at Edwards Air Force Base in
California.
   ``The Defense Department has determined that the longer we can
keep the launch time and the type of payload under wraps, the less
chance anyone has of tracking it and learning what it is,'' Warren
said.
   Published reports and sources who requested anonymity have said
the astronauts will put into orbit a sophisticated satellite to
gather intelligence over the Soviet Union, China, the Middle East
and other areas of military interest.
   Commanding the crew is Air Force Col. Brewster Shaw, a veteran
of two earlier shuttle flights, including a 1983 trip on Columbia.
The other crew members are Navy Cmdr. Richard Richards, Navy Cmdr.
David Leestma, Army Lt. Col. James Adamson and Air Force Maj. Mark
Brown.
   Columbia, the oldest shuttle, will be making its eighth flight
but its first since it was launched just 16 days before the
Challenger explosion that killed seven astronauts on Jan. 28, 1986.
Following the accident, NASA concentrated first on making safety
modifications to sister ships Discovery and Atlantis, and each has
made two space trips since flights resumed last September.
   Returning the veteran Columbia to flight status will give NASA
three orbiters to handle an increasing flight rate. Three more
missions are planned this year and nine in 1990.
   Asked by reporters Saturday if he had confidence in riding in a
shuttle that had been grounded so long, commander Shaw replied:
``Absolutely, you bet I do. I wouldn't fly it if I didn't. ... I
flew Columbia a long time ago. It's a great machine and it will be
great again.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
