<FIRST>u i PM-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru a0485 08-07 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0485,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rocket Barrage Around Hotel For Second Day</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with hotel hit, details of injured.
Pickup 5th pvs, ``A Foreign ...' ^By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rocket barrage pounded northwest
Kabul for the second day today, sending frightened residents
running for cover, damaging the city's only luxury hotel and
injuring several people.
   Officials at Avicina and Alibad hospitals said they treated four
victims, including a 10-year-old boy who lost both legs. The Red
Cross hospital also reported several injuries.
   In less than an hour, about 15 rockets struck within a mile of
the hilltop Continental Hotel. One hit the hotel, carving a
two-foot-wide hole, crashing into the fifth-floor presidential
suite and setting it ablaze before plunging through to the fourth
floor. The rooms were unoccupied and no one was injured.
   Later in the afternoon, several more rockets fell, one setting
off a blaze after apparently igniting some fuel in a business and
residential area beneath the Afghan TV broadcasting tower, perched
on one of the hills surrounding this mile-high capital.
   On Sunday, more than 20 rockets struck within a mile of the
240-room Continental Hotel.
   A Foreign Ministry spokesman said U.S.-backed guerrillas trying
to oust the Soviet-supported government apparently were targeting
the Continental because they thought Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
A. Shevardnadze stayed there when he visited the Afghan capital
Sunday.
   Shevardnadze arrived Sunday morning and left that evening, the
Soviet Embassy said. He met twice with President Najib but there
was no immediate word on the outcome of the talks.
   Bakhtar, the Afghan News Agency, said 38 rockets hit Kabul
Sunday, killing nine people and injuring 38. Four major hospitals
reported 52 injured.
   The Continental, once owned by the Intercontinental chain, shook
several times as the rockets, with their distinctive whistle and
booms, struck in rapid succession. The lobby was filled with smoke
and dozens of windows were shattered.
   Several rockets also apparently were aimed at Kabul's main grain
silo, where several hundred trucks were lined up waiting to be
unloaded. One appeared to hit close to the silo's perimeter and
another several blocks away in a residential area.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani has accused the
guerrillas of targeting the silo to try to starve the capital's
2.25 million residents.
   Several other rockets fell in the Karte Parwan district, not far
from the British High Commission, which was evacuated early this
year.
   The government has extended the summer holiday because of the
intensified rocketing.
   No group has claimed responsibility for the latest rocketing but
the guerrillas _ who call themselves mujahedeen, or Islamic holy
warriors _ have said they carried out previous attacks.
   The insurgents say they aim at military targets and have accused
the government of firing rockets at civilian targets, a charge the
government denies.
   Kabul has been subjected to almost daily rocketing since late
June. According to U.N. sources, 281 people were killed and 745
injured between June 25 and Aug. 1 by rockets and in a car bombing
in the capital.
</TEXT>
