<FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-89 1018EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Japan     08-07 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leadership Front-Runner Urges Greater World Role for Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The front-runner in Japan's race for prime minister
said today the nation should play a greater role in the world,
including helping Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reform
efforts.
   A second candidate suggested a ``Global New Deal'' policy using
Japan's wealth to benefit other nations.
   All three candidates agreed Japan's governing party is in need
of rescue following money and sex scandals which contributed to its
losing its majority in Parliament's upper house. Voters also were
angered by a new 3 percent sales tax.
   Prime Minister Sousuke Uno announced his resignation to take
responsibility for his Liberal Democratic Party's July 23 election
defeat.
   On Tuesday, the party votes for a new leader who will become
prime minister because of the governing party's majority in the
more powerful lower house.
   The candidates presented their positions today in speeches to
party members that were nationally televised.
   Toshiki Kaifu, 58, seen as most likely to win because of backing
by major party factions, said, ``It is not enough for Japan to
simply maintain the security treaty with the United States and not
to play a more responsible role now that Japan has grown so
powerful and economically affluent.''
   ``We are responsible for fulfilling the world's expectations of
Japan,'' said Kaifu, a former education minister.
   Aside from the Soviet Union's restructuring plan, Kaifu
suggested Japan could contribute to the opening of East European
countries.
   He stressed his determination to rescue the governing party,
adding, ``I believe the LDP's resurrection is the only way for
Japan to maintain freedom, democracy, peace and affluence.''
   Kaifu is running against Shintaro Ishihara, 56, a former
transport minister from the party's nationalist wing, and former
Welfare Minister Yoshiro Hayashi, 62. None of the three has a
strong personal power base in the party, but most senior party
leaders have been tainted by an influence-peddling scandal.
   Parliament is expected to confirm the new party leader as prime
minister on Wednesday. He will be Japan's third prime minister in
slightly more than two months. Noboru Takeshita stepped down on
June 2 because of the influence-buying scandal.
   Hayashi proposed the ``Global New Deal'' to aid other nations,
but gave no details.
   He also stressed the need to clean up the party image.
   ``Public anger toward the party has not calmed down even after
our election defeat,'' he said. ``There seems to be persistent
distrust and anger among the people.''
   Ishihara, a best-selling novelist, declared, ``The party's
leadership still lacks a sense of crisis. It seems as though the
prime concern for many party members is no more than
self-protection. I think the LDP's decline has come to the point
where it can't fall any further.''
   Ishihara is co-author of a recently published book, ``The Japan
That Can Say No,'' and he repeated that theme of independence today.
   ``I am never an anti-American, but we have to get up and say
what we have to say. We should cooperate when we can cooperate and
we have to say no when unreasonable demands are made,'' he said.
</TEXT>
