<FIRST>r a PM-ToughestCop     08-07 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Toughest Cop,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Simi Valley Officer Wins `Toughest Cop Alive' Competition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIMI VALLEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   He's getting older and he trains on
cookies for breakfast and hamburgers for lunch, by Mike Bender is
still the toughest cop alive.
   That's the title he brought back from the World Police and Fire
Games, a week-long competition last week in Vancouver, British
Columbia. Bender has won the title every time since the biennial
games began in 1985.
   ``It was a killer,'' he said. ``But it was worth it because this
shows that cops from a small town can beat the entire Los Angeles
Police Department.''
   Bender is a detective with the Simi Valley Police Department in
this suburb of about 100,000 residents 35 miles from downtown Los
Angeles.
   Although he's 34, Bender asked to enter the category for men 29
and under _ considered the competition's toughest. He then climbed
a 20-foot rope faster, heaved a shot put farther, ran faster and
did more pullups _ 38 _ than any of his competitors. There were 166
competitors from U.S. police departments big and small.
   Bender said this year's competition may be his last. ``I've had
my fill of competing,'' he said. ``I look forward to helping judge
the contest in 1991.''
   Sgt. Tony Harper, Bender's former supervisor, is skeptical,
noting the detective has said the same thing before.
   ``One thing about police work is that we keep getting older, but
the crooks are always about 19 or 20,'' Harper said. ``It's nice to
have someone fit like Mike around.''
</TEXT>
