<HEAD>Town Official Fears Missing Pet Was `Dognapped'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to CORRECT population to 6,700 sted 3,700;
PICKS UP 3rd graf, `Johanson said ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOPKINTON, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Town Council president says there's
been no sign of her dog since the animal disappeared a week ago and
a caller demanded she resign to get her pet back.
   Police in this town of 6,700 said they have no firm evidence
Sandra Johanson's 7-year-old golden retriever Kelly was dognapped
but that there's a good chance the call was genuine.
   Johanson said her two dogs went for a romp outdoors a week ago
today, and Kelly failed to return. Shortly afterward, she said, an
unidentified male caller told her, ``Get off the council and you'll
have your dog.''
   ``All I can say is that my husband and I and the kids have been
out (searching) constantly and have turned up nothing,'' said
Johanson, whose love for her dogs is well known in the town.
   The council president, a Republican serving her third two-year
term, has waged political battles with a former manager of the town
dump and a former member of the Conservation Commission, but she
said she didn't think the dog's disappearance was related.
   Police Chief George H. Weeden said there haven't been many leads
to follow. Weeden said the call was probably genuine because
Johanson received it before it was widely known that the dog was
missing.
   The dognapper could face charges of theft and extortion, Weeden
said.
