<FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-89 1054EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka     08-07 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>India Withdraws 875 More Soldiers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   India withdrew 875 more soldiers from
Sri Lanka as President Ranasinghe Premadasa called a special
Cabinet meeting to discuss negotiations to pull out all 45,000
Indian peackeepers on the islands.
   An Indian High Commission spokesman confirmed the troops, from
the Mahar regiment, left for home from the northern seaport of
Kankesanthurai on Sunday. The spokesman, who can not be named under
standing regulations, described their withdrawal as a gesture of
sincerity.
   The two countries have been at loggerheads since Premadasa
demanded India withdraw troops dispatched two years ago to enforce
an Indian-brokered peace accord to end a six-year insurgency by
separatist Tamils fighting in northeast Sri Lanka.
   The accord was rejected by the biggest Tamil group, the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam.
   Sinhalese extremists from the People's Liberation Front, angered
by government concessions to Tamils and an Indian troop presence
they say compromises Sri Lanka's independence, launched a violent
campaign against Premadasa's Sinhalese-dominated government.
   Premadasa sent his Foreign Minister Ranjan Wijeratne and a
six-member delegation to New Delhi on July 29 to discuss a time
frame for the pullout of the rest of the troops.
   The president today called a special meeting of his Cabinet to
discuss Wijeratne's talks with Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi and
other Indian officials.
   Sinhalese radicals killed 20 people in the past 24 hours,
military officials said today.
   The victims included four policemen killed when their vehicle
was blown up by remote-controlled explosives near Ratnapura, 45
miles southeast of Colombo, and a government supporter in the
Colombo suburb of Bandaragama.
   Government troops killed a suspected radical in north central
Polonnaruwa district, the officials said.
   At least 4,000 people, mainly government officials and
supporters, have been killed in the two-year Sinhalese rebellion.
The Tamil insurgency has claimed 11,000 lives since 1983.
   Tamils form 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people and
accuse the majority Sinhalese of discriminating against them.
   Premadasa two months ago demanded India withdraw all its troops
by July 29, the second anniversary of the peace accord.
   India made a token withdrawal of 620 soldiers by the deadline,
averting a possible showdown between the neighbors.
   India has linked the troop withdrawal to more powers for the
Tamil-dominated provincial administration in the northeast.
   After the New Delhi talks ended Friday, India made a conditional
offer to withdraw 1,500 troops a week, Sri Lankan Foreign Ministry
officials said earlier.
</TEXT>
