<FIRST>r a PM-SaludaPool 1stLd-Writethru a0492 08-07 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Saluda Pool, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0492,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Once-Segregated Swimming Pool Opens to Both Blacks and Whites</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, `A few ...' to CLARIFY that membership fee
was prorated.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH GROAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALUDA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blacks are now swimming in what had been a
whites-only pool, and some said the opening of the waters was long
overdue.
   ``It's about time,'' said Bernard Daniel, 34, who stopped on his
way to a wedding Saturday to witness the end of the Saluda Swim and
Tennis Club's segregation policy.
   A few black families bought memberships, which were sold for
half price because the summer is half over. About five blacks swam,
as did about the same number of whites. The parking lot was filled,
though, with people who stopped for a glimpse.
   Janet Sibert brought her two children and purchased a membership
Saturday. ``I'm happy the kids will be able to swim,'' said Mrs.
Sibert, who works in Saluda but lives in Greenwood, about 28 miles
away.
   ``I want my children to feel good about themselves and know they
can swim where they want to,'' she said.
   The pool in this town 45 miles south of Columbia was closed July
26 following publicity about the club's refusal July 13 to admit
three black youths who were part of a church group that had
arranged to use the pool.
   The land on which the club stands was deeded to the town in 1933
with the stipulation that it was for the use by the ``white
children'' of the county and town of Saluda. The stipulation
remained when the town sold the land to the Saluda Jaycees for $5
in 1955.
   The club rents the land from the Jaycees and enforced the rule.
After the church group complained, the Jaycees ordered the pool
closed until it was desegregated.
   Daniel said that when he and a friend tried to obtain a pool
membership three years ago, they were refused.
   ``I was told it was for white men,'' recalled Daniel, who is
black. Nothing was done at the time, although there were ``people
here who knew it was wrong,'' he said.
   Robert Booth, president of the pool's seven-member board of
directors, said he was pleased that the pool opened under the
desegregation policy.
   ``It's going well,'' he said. ``I feel like (blacks) will start
coming to the pool.''
   Jamie Willis, 17, who is white, said they probably wouldn't.
   ``They think they're not wanted there,'' said Miss Willis, who
was watching and said she was not a club member.
   She also said that the $80 seasonal membership fee might be too
expensive for many people in the mostly rural town of about 3,000
people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
