<FIRST>u i PM-Cambodia-UN 1stLd-Writethru a0540 08-07 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia-UN, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0540,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Team Arrives in Cambodia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS one graf for 6th pvs, `The U.S....' to CORRECT U.S. to
U.N. team; pick up 7th graf, `All factions...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.N. team arrived in Cambodia today
to investigate the feasibility of forming an international body for
monitoring a pullout of Vietnamese troops, Cambodia's official news
agency said.
   The fact-finding team was sent by an international conference on
Cambodia that opened July 30 in Paris. It is to report back late
this month to the conference, which is trying to end the nearly
11-year Cambodia war.
   The 15-member U.N. team arrived in the Cambodian capital, Phnom
Penh, from Bangkok, Thailand, said the SPK report, which was
monitored in Bangkok.
   The unarmed team seeks to gather information helpful in forming
an international body to monitor the withdrawal. Vietnam, whose
invasion began the war, says it will withdraw all its 26,000 troops
by late September.
   However, without a settlement, the pullout would leave
Cambodia's Vietnamese-installed government fighting a coalition of
three guerrilla groups led by Prince Norodom Sihanouk.
   The U.N. team's leader, Lt. Gen. Martin O. Vadset of Norway,
said Sunday he expects his group to have no difficulties.
   ``All factions and neighboring countries have been very
forthcoming in giving support and have been very helpful to the
delegation,'' he said.
   He said the delegation would spend eight days in Cambodia, then
return for talks with Thai authorities and visit the Thai-Cambodian
border. The frontier area is base for the guerrilla coalition and
guerrilla-controlled camps housing 300,000 refugees.
</TEXT>
