<FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-89 1608EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-UtahFusion     08-07 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Utah Fusion,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Panel Approves Cold Fusion Funding</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEG McENTEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The University of Utah's cold fusion
program cleared a major hurdle Monday when a state panel voted to
release $4.5 million for research into the phenomenon and its
potential as a new energy source.
   The 7-1 vote, with one abstention, reflected the objections of
the only two scientists on the panel. The vote allows the
university to fund a National Cold Fusion Institute for research
into fusion and its practical application.
   ``There's going to be lots of hard work to be done,'' said Chase
Peterson, university president. ``It's like being pleased to be
asked to plow 100 acres of sugar beets. But I'm pleased.''
   James Brophy, vice president for research, also announced that
General Electric had signed an agreement providing for
``substantial financial participation,'' but he declined to
elaborate.
   University officials had hoped for months that the Fusion-Energy
Advisory Council, charged with confirming the feasibility of cold
fusion and disbursing a $5 million legislative appropriation for
research, would unanimously approve release of the remaining $4.5
million.
   However, the panel voted 7-1 for approval, with Wilford Hansen,
a Utah State University physicist, abstaining. The lone dissenter
was university provost Karen Morse, a chemist who said she would
have preferred more of the money being spent on science instead of
facilities and administration.
   Of cold fusion, Morse said, ``We can only have verification when
a full understanding of the science is in. I have concerns about
putting money into things other than research.''
   Morse, saying she did not object to the funding per se, moved
unsuccessfully for a line-item review of the proposed budget by the
full council. The council's four-member executive committee already
had screened the budget and recommended passage to the full body.
   Hansen echoed Morse's concern about confirming the research of
University of Utah chemist B. Stanley Pons and his British
colleague, Martin Fleischmann, who claim to have produced a
sustained nuclear fusion reaction in a laboratory beaker.
   Hansen recalled the scientific community's general skepticism
about the experiment and said it would have to be generally
duplicated in order to erase the doubts.
   ``As soon as we have the science, it will send a shock wave
around the world,'' Hansen said. ``You don't need hyperbolic public
promotion.''
   The two chemists announced in March that they had sustained a
fusion reaction by running an electrical current between platinum
and palladium electrodes immersed in heavy water. They later said
the table-top, room temperature experiments generated up to about
100 times the current charging them.
   Fusion involves the combining of atoms and should be safer than
fission, atom-splitting used to produce nuclear power.
   But at subsequent scientific gatherings, Pons and Fleischmann
were accused of shoddy research and criticized for not publishing
enough information to enable others to duplicate their results.
   Council Chairman Raymond Hixson acknowledged the criticism, but
said reports that several universities already had duplicated the
work was impetus for releasing the money.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890807-0086 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-89 1614EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Murder-Albany     08-07 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Murder-Albany,0569</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crime Rate Statistics Add Twist To Albany Mayoral Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An FBI report listing the Albany metropolitan
area as the nation's most murderous came just two days before the
mayor faces a re-election challenge.
   Mayor Larry Bays told voters in the southern Georgia city that
the FBI murder statistics issued Sunday were misleading and that
challenger Tommy Coleman hurt the city's image by capitalizing on
the murder rate.
   Whoever wins Tuesday's Democratic primary will have a lock on
the mayor's office _ no Republican is running in the Nov. 7 general
election.
   The latest FBI Uniform Crime Report shows the Albany area had
24.1 murders per 100,000 residents in 1988. The New York area was
second with 22.7. The New York region reported 3,577 murders to 29
in the Albany area, but the relatively tiny Albany metro population
_ 120,560 in relation to New York's 8.6 million _ gave it the
higher rate.
   Assistant Police Chief Bob Boren said 70 percent of Albany's
murders could be attributed to the drug trade. Police say crack
cocaine has become pervasive in the city's poor neighborhoods.
   Coleman, a bank executive, originally reacted to the report by
saying, ``People are living in fear. They have deadbolt locks,
security bars on their windows and chain link fences around their
front yards.''
   Bays said there was no fair way to compare Albany and New York,
and by Monday, he was trying to turn the issue in his favor.
   In an interview with The Albany Herald, he blasted Coleman for
``this mishandling of the FBI's release of its crime report and the
irresponsible statements that he made about that.''
   Coleman said he regretted that too much had been made of the
murder statistics.
   ``Albany is no different than any other city in the nation,'' he
told the newspaper. ``They all have problems with drugs, crime and
they all have certain depressed areas where people have been living
there for a long time and are afraid.''
   Boren noted his officers had solved all the city's murders in
1987 and 1988. ``They might commit the crimes, but they're not
walking around after they commit them,'' he said.
   In other major crimes, the FBI said, Albany had 92 forcible
rapes, 433 robberies, 429 aggravated assaults, 4,493 larcenies and
354 motor vehicle thefts.
   To combat crime, the police formed a major crime squad to focus
on violent offenses, and the city and surrounding Dougherty County
organized a consolidated drug squad.
   In addition, officers have cracked down on loitering in
high-crime areas and are enforcing an ordinance aimed at
eliminating fortified buildings that could be used for drug dealing.
   ``We're certainly not satisfied,'' Bays said of the city's crime
prevention efforts. ``That's why we have the major crimes task
force.''
   Coleman said he favors hiring more police officers, opening
precinct stations and putting more cops on the street where they
can develop a better rapport with neighborhood residents.
   ``I'm committed to a safer Albany,'' he said. ``We've got to do
a better job with our people by providing more jobs. We've got very
high unemployment. Unemployment breeds despair and despair breeds
violence.''
   Albany suffered a serious economic setback a few years ago when
two major manufacturing plants shut down, eliminating 2,000 jobs.
</TEXT>
