<FIRST>u a AM-Bush     08-07 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Enlists Boy Scouts in War on Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOWLING GREEN, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush exhorted thousands of
Boy Scouts on Monday to steer their peers away from ``this scourge
called drugs.''
   Bush, becoming the first president since Lyndon B. Johnson to
attend a Boy Scout Jamboree, told more than 30,000 scouts and
leaders encamped at Fort A.P. Hill that keeping drugs out of
America's schools was ``perhaps the greatest challenge of our
times.''
   As Bush's Marine One helicopter landed, loudspeakers blared the
theme music from Indiana Jones from a giant stage, drawing cheers
from the huge crowd clad in green and olive. Bush described it as
an ``unbelievable gathering.''
   Bush called drugs ``a form of pollution, a poisoning of the
mind, a corruption of the very soul of young America.''
   Bush said the Boy Scouts have helped out ``through times of
disaster, from fires to flash floods'' and during wartime.
   Now, he said, the organization has already ``taken on a new
struggle to defeat what you call the five `unacceptables' _
illiteracy, unemployment, child abuse, drug abuse and hunger.''
   The president cited recent statistics showing an overall drop of
40 percent in the number of Americans using drugs, but added, ``we
cannot yet claim victory.
   ``The number of people addicted to cocaine and crack has almost
doubled. We must work harder,'' he said. ``I am especially looking
to you to encourage friends to refuse drugs _ any illegal drugs.''
   He cited a first-person account last week in The Wall Street
Journal by reporter Ronald Shafer about how drugs and alcohol led
to the death of his son Ryan at age 16.
   ``There are thousands of Ryans across America, thousands of
young men and women who are in danger of losing their future, their
very lives to this scourge called drugs,'' said Bush.
   ``Ask yourself if you know someone like Ryan Shafer. And if so,
have you done everything you can to help him or her?'' he said.
   Bush, an avid fisherman, told the youths of the pleasure he has
found in the outdoors.
   ``Whatever you love to do _ whether it's hiking, hunting or
kayaking _ hang on to it. ... '' Bush advised the scouts. ``If you
stay true to the hobbies of your youth, you will find a source of
relaxation and replenishment that will never fail you.''
   Bush brought three Eagle Scouts with him from his top staff _
Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner and White House aides
Andrew Card and Robert Gates _ and said it was ``no coincidence
that half of all astronauts were once scouts.''
   He put in a pitch for his recently enuciated goals of
reinvigorating the space program, including seeking ``to establish
an outpost on the moon and explore the mysteries of Mars'' in the
next century.
   ``You are privileged to be the generation that will witness the
first large movement of men and women into space,'' he said.
   The scouts, from across the United States and abroad, end their
seven-day 12th National Jamboree on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
