<SECOND>AM-US-Cuba,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Criticizes Cuba for Arrests of Activists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States on Monday condemned Cuba's
arrest of four human rights activists, calling the action a
``flagrant human rights violation.''
   Richard Boucher, the State Department spokesman, said Elizardo
Sanchez, head of the Cuban Commission of Human Rights and National
Conciliation, was arrested along with three colleagues.
   Representatives of Sanchez' organization said he was taken into
custody by state security police in a pre-dawn raid on his house.
Sanchez had recently complained about human rights in Cuba to
American reporters.
   ``These arrests come as yet another flagrant human rights
violation in the Cuban government's renewed crackdown against human
rights activists,'' Boucher said.
   ``We hope concerned members of the international community,
including the United Nations, will join us in condemning not only
Sanchez' arrest, but also the continued imprisonment of other
prominent human rights leaders,'' Boucher said.
   In his meetings with American reporters, Sanchez characterized
the executions of four Cuban officials convicted of drug
trafficking last month as ``assassinations.''
   He also claimed that the regime of Cuban leader Fidel Castro has
waged an intensified campaign against that country's human rights
organizations.
