<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia-UN     08-07 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia-UN,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Fact-Finding Team Reaches Cambodia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A United Nations team arrived in
Cambodia Monday to study the feasibility of forming an
international body to monitor the Vietnamese military withdrawal,
the official Cambodian news agency SPK said.
   The 15-member team went to the Cambodian capital, Phnom Penh,
from Bangkok, Thailand.
   It was sent by the international conference on Cambodia that
opened July 30 in Paris. It is to report back later this month to
the conference, which is seeking an end to the war that began with
Vietnam's invasion of Cambodia nearly 11 years ago.
   The information gathered by the team is to be used to establish
a group to monitor what Vietnam says will be the pullout of its
26,000 military personnel by late September.
   If the Paris conference fails to achieve a settlement to the war
the withdrawal would leave Cambodia's Vietnamese-installed
government fighting a coalition of three guerrilla groups.
   The report by SPK quoted Prime Minister Hun Sen as saying his
government would facilitate the U.N. team's work.
   ``The mission will also examine the state of roads, airports and
communications in Cambodia,'' the report said. ``The officers and
the civilian members of the team are to wear blue berets and U.N.
insignia but they are not armed.''
   Lt. Gen. Martin O. Vadset of Norway, the leader of the mission,
said, ``All factions and neighboring countries have been very
forthcoming in giving support and have been very helpful to the
delegation, so we have no doubt we will be able to do whatever we
like.''
   Vadset, 58, is chief of staff of the U.N. Truce Supervision
Organization in the Middle East.
   He said his team is to spend about eight days in Cambodia, then
return to hold talks with Thai authorities and visit the
Thai-Cambodian border.
   Most of Cambodia is controlled by the Phnom Penh government.
Rebel-controlled refugee camps, which house about 300,000
civilians, are strung along the Thai-Cambodian border.
   Fighting the Phnom Penh government and Vietnamese are guerrillas
of the radical Khmer Rouge, an anti-communist force and those loyal
to Prince Norodom Sihanouk.
</TEXT>
