<FIRST>r i AM-Bloch     08-07 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bloch,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paper Reports Second Transfer in Bloch Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   French and U.S. agents watched a
suspected KGB operative transfer a travel case he had received from
Felix Bloch to another KGB agent, a newspaper reported Monday.
   Also on Monday, Bloch, a former U.S. diplomat, was quoted in a
magazine interview as avoiding a direct question about whether he
had spied.
   Bloch, 54, worked from 1980 to 1987 at the U.S. Embassy in
Vienna and served as its No. 2 official. He was suspended by the
State Department on June 22 but no charges have been filed.
   The French magazine Paris-Match and the U.S. television network
ABC reported last week that a suspected Soviet agent picked up
Bloch's travel bag after the two men dined together at a restaurant
in Paris.
   Paris-Match reported the suspected Soviet agent was a man using
the name Reino Gikman on a Finnish passport.
   The Austrian daily Der Standard reported that Gikman later
passed the bag to another suspected KGB agent.
   According to the Paris-Match report, the first transaction took
place last May 14 and was filmed and photographed by French agents.
   Der Standard, attributing its report to ``secret agent
circles,'' said that the next day Gikman gave the bag to a man
identified by the French counterespionage agency as a KGB agent. It
said that agent took it out of the country.
   The paper said the transfer was observed by French and U.S.
agents as well as KGB agents.
   The reports did not say what was in the travel bag.
   In a telephone interview reported in Monday's Austrian news
magazine Profil Bloch avoided a direct answer to a question.
   Profil said journalist Josef Votzi asked Bloch, ``If you are
really innocent, a one-sentence comment would suffice: I am accused
unjustly of espionage, I was not and am not a spy.''
   The magazine reported Bloch replied, ``There are accusations;
there are no proofs. One has to prove my guilt.''
</TEXT>
