<FIRST>r w AM-Turtles-Shrimpers     08-07 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turtles-Shrimpers,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mosbacher Proposes 105-Minute Trawls</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher, told by a
judge to protect endangered sea turtles, told shrimp fishermen
Monday they must inspect their nets every 105 minutes for trapped
turtles.
   Environmentalists said that interval was too long and promised
to oppose Mosbacher in court.
   The Commerce Department said the trawling time limitations,
which take effect Tuesday and will be in place at least through
Sept. 7, will protect the Kemp's ridley turtle better than turtle
excluder devices, which shrimp fishermen loathe.
   The department says the turtles can survive submerged for 90
minutes. Environmentalists say the department's own studies show
that one in four sea turtles will drown during a tow time of 105
minutes.
   The new regulation established a 105-minute cycle for shrimpers
_ 7{ minutes to get their nets in the water, 90 minutes to trawl
and 7{ minutes to retreive the nets.
   ``We don't think the secretary's proposed regulations comply
with the law and we're going to challenge it in court,'' said
National Wildlife Federation spokesman Charlie Miller.
   The department predicted compliance with the trawling time
limitations would be far better than with the excluder devices.
   ``Because there is so much opposition to the (excluder)
regulations, compliance has been very low in some areas,'' the
department said in a document filed in federal court here. ``It is,
therefore, likely that many turtles are dying in the nets of those
trawlers who are refusing to use'' the devices.
   U.S. District Court Judge Thomas Hogan, who last week ordered
Mosbacher to begin protecting sea turtles from drowning in
shrimpers' nets by Monday _ after the secretary suspended
enforcement of the excluder device law July 24 following massive
shrimper protests _ had not ruled on the Commerce plan by late in
the day.
   Conservationists said the judge was not expected to rule before
midweek.
   Officials will take public comment on the rules through Aug. 21
to determine whether the trawling time restrictions should be
continued or modified ``in light of conservation needs of sea
turtle populations and the economics of the shrimp fishing
industry.''
   Tom Miller, a spokesman for the Center for Marine Conservation,
said the restrictions are unenforceable and that the Kemp's ridley
must surface frequently to ventilate its lungs.
   ``We believe the tow-time restrictions condemn the sea turtles
to extinction,'' Miller said. ``Tow times are not the answer.''
   Judge Hogan issued his ruling in a suit filed by the National
Wildlife Federation, which wants the excluder regulations enforced.
   Mosbacher suspended the regulations after shrimpers protested
their use by blockading Texas Gulf Coast shipping channels.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
