<FIRST>u w AM-US-Hostages 1stLd-Writethru a0653 08-07 0738</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Hostages, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0653,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>FBI Says Body in Tape Apparently Higgins'; Bush Praises Marine</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS date of kidnapping in 9th graf, Higgins, head</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI said Monday it believes the videotape
released last week in Beirut shows the body of American hostage
William Higgins hanging from a rope, but the agency offered no
conclusion as to the cause or timing of death.
   President Bush, who praised Marine Lt. Col. Higgins publicly
during the day as a ``symbol of courage,'' telephoned Mrs. Higgins
to offer private condolences and tell her the United States is
still seeking full details on her husband.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Gen. Al Gray, the
commandant of the Marine Corps, had informed Higgins' wife of the
results of the FBI analysis of the videotape ``purported to be of
Lt. Col. Higgins.''
   ``Presidet Bush called Mrs. Higgins at about 2 p.m. to offer his
support and encouragement. The president said the U.S. government
will continue to do all it can to obtain a full accounting of what
happened to her husband,'' Fitzwater said.
   The FBI said its forensic experts have concluded ``within a
reasonable degree of medical certainty that the person depicted in
the videotape is dead.''
   ``Although a positive identification could not be made, numerous
observable characteristics were noted indicating that the person
depicted in the videotape is Lt. Col. Higgins,'' the FBI said.
   A law enforcement source, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said FBI experts were unable to determine the time of Higgins'
death from their examination of the videotape.
   The tape showed a man, bound and gagged, hanging by a rope from
his neck.
   Higgins, head of a 75-member United Nations peacekeeping team,
was kidnapped in south Lebanon on Feb. 17, 1988.
   The president paid tribute to Higgins at a ceremony at Ft. Myer
in nearby Arlington, Va., marking the 200th anniversary of the
Department of War, forerunner to the Pentagon.
   Bush used the occasion to press for his defense priorities,
including mobile nuclear missiles, the B-2 bomber and the Strategic
Defense Initiative, all threatened with budget cuts on Capitol Hill.
   With the Defense Department's top civilian and military brass
seated behind him, Bush offered a salute to ``every brave American
who ever served'' in peace and wartime.
   Then, in a voice that broke, he added:
   ``We cannot leave here today without pausing to salute one who
stands as the symbol of the courage that burns in the breast of
every American in uniform, one Marine who has been very much in our
thoughts, Lt. Col. Higgins, William Richard Higgins.''
   Higgins' captors said they hanged him last Monday in retaliation
for the Israeli kidnapping of a Moslem cleric, Sheik Abdul Karim
Obeid. The terrorists had made previous death threats against
Higgins, calling him a spy.
   Israeli government officials said their sources indicated
Higgins had been killed some time ago.
   Fitzwater said now is a time of ``monitoring and watching'' at
the White House as the Bush administration pursues diplomatic
efforts to free hostages in Lebanon. Eight additional Americans are
being held, and a half-dozen other Westerners.
   Fitzwater said Bush was ``cautiously optimistic,'' but expects
it will take ``a longer period of time rather than shorter.''
   ``There are a lot of ideas being floated, a lot of exchanges
being made. ... We see ideas coming out from Iran, from Syria,
Algeria, Israel, the United States, everybody,'' said Fitzwater.
   The pro-Iranian Revolutionary Justice Organization said Sunday
it would release another American hostage, Joseph Cicippio, if
Israel frees the Moslem cleric and hundreds of other Lebanese and
Palestinian prisoners.
   Fitzwater said of the White House refusal to comment on that
offer: ``We have to be very careful of what we say. ... Often you
can cut off those kinds of channels and communications if you
comment prematurely in public.''
   There is no change in the U.S. policy of refusing to negotiate
with terrorists, said Fitzwater.
   ``We have always said our policy is to talk to anyone who has
information about our hostages, to discuss any possibility of
release, to pursue every avenue of knowledge and information that
might lead to their release and that's what we're doing,'' he said.
   Richard Boucher, a State Department spokesman, said the U.S.
role ``remains one of active diplomacy.'' He added, ``We're
continuing to be in contact with various parties in the region and
with international organizations.''
</TEXT>
