<FIRST>r i AM-Tunisia-PLO     08-07 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tunisia-PLO,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fatah Hardliners Call for Military Action</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hard-line factions within Fatah, the main
unit of the Palestine Liberation Organization, on Monday renewed a
call for military action against Israel outside the
Israeli-occupied territories, PLO sources said.
   It was part of a draft resolution to be submitted for a vote
before about 1,000 Fatah members attending a five-day congress in
the Tunisian capital.
   The move conflicts with attempts by PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat
to adopt a more moderate approach to solving the issue of
Palestinian sovereignty.
   The Palestine National Congress, the PLO's parliament, declared
Palestinian independence last November. Arafat then declared that
the PLO would restrict armed actions to Israeli-occupied
territories, although the exact meaning of ``occupied territories''
was vague.
   Arafat's stand led to talks with the United States and weakened
Israel's refusal to deal with the PLO on grounds the PLO is a
terrorist organization.
   PLO sources at the congress, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said Monday's call to arms was included in the draft resolution
over the objections of more moderate Fatah members.
   They said the draft also rejects Israel's proposal for elections
in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip but supports
Arafat's acceptance of elections after Israeli troops withdraw
under United Nations supervision.
   The meeting, the first Fatah congress in nine years, opened
Friday and was closed to journalists after opening remarks by
Arafat and Tunisian President Zine Abidine Ben Ali.
   In Amman, the capital of Jordan, a senior PLO official said
Monday his organization will transfer a fund headquarters to Amman
from Abu Dhabi in the United Arab Emirates to help boost Jordan's
troubled economy, .
   The official, also speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Arafat would visit Jordan next week to inaugurate the Palestine
National Fund's new headquarters.
   The official Jordan news agency Petra reported Monday that
Jordan agreed to the PLO decision.
   The fund functions as Fatah's treasury. It was moved from Amman
in 1986 after relations between the PLO and Jordan soured.
Relations improved after King Hussein's decision in July 1988 to
renounce sovereignty over the West bank in favor of the PLO. Israel
captured the West Bank from Jordan in the 1967 war.
</TEXT>
