<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     08-07 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Attack Intelligence Agency, U.S. Center</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small band of anti-government
students attacked the headquarters of the national intelligence
agency Monday with firebombs and demanded it be closed down.
   In Taegu, several hundred students hurled rocks and shattered
windows at guardposts at the U.S. Cultural Center Sunday night and
clashed with riot police, according to the Yonhap news agency.
   The attack on the U.S. facility followed a rally at Kyongbuk
University to protest what some students said is government
suppression of a new teachers' union. Six students were arrested,
but no injuries were reported.
   On Monday ten students hurled firebombs into the compound of the
Agency for National Security Planning in eastern Seoul, Yonhap
reported.
   ``Disband NSP'' the students shouted, according to the news
agency. It said the students painted slogans on the compound walls
before fleeing.
   Police reported two demonstrators were arrested..
   Kim Dae-jung, leader of the opposition Party for Peace and
Democracy, said Monday that ``anti-democratic forces within the
ruling party are threatening democracy.''
   He said a crackdown on dissidents, the investigation of three
people for making visits to communist North Korea and his detention
by the national security agency has given ``an anti-democratic
faction within the ruling camp'' more power.
   ``Politics by the security agency'' threatens to stem the
nation's move toward democracy, he said, and the ``faction that
favored reforms has become weak.''
   Kim was detained by the intelligence agency for 22 hours last
week for questioning in connection with an illegal trip to North
Korea by a lawmaker in his party.
   Kim said his party, as the leading opposition party, had been
singled out for harrassment by intelligence agents.
   President Roh Tae-woo, in a nationwide radio address Monday,
urged radical students, a small but active minority on university
campuses, to end violent protests. The radical students have little
popular support because of their violent tactics.
   Roh said ``the reckless acts of a small number of radical
leftists are deepening distrust and confrontation and obstructing
reunification with the north.''
