<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Army     08-07 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Army,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Forty Percent of Future Recruits Surveyed Say They Hate Arabs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A survey of 5,300 future Israeli army recruits
showed that 40 percent ``hate most or all Arabs'' and 90 percent
would volunteer if they were not drafted, Israel army radio said
Monday.
   It also indicated most high school students believe there will
be another Arab-Israeli war, the radio said, but did not give a
percentage figures.
   The survey, the first of its kind since the Palestinian uprising
against Israeli occupatio of West Bank and Gaza Strip began 20
months ago, was conducted last year by a private research company
for the Education Ministry.
   It said 42 percent identified themselves as representing the
political right and 34 percent as leftists.
   ``I think if we asked the general population the same questions,
we would get similar answers,'' said Avraham Amir, director-general
of the Education Ministry.
   He said the army and government try to educate soldiers not to
hate Arabs, despite the continuing conflict.
   Reuven Gel of the private Israel Institute for Military Studies,
which conducted the survey, said researchers interviewed 5,300
students aged 16 to 18 from high schools across the country.
   Israeli men are drafted at 18 for a three-year tour of duty and
continue doing reserve service of up to 45 days a year until age
55. Women serve for two years and are not required to serve in the
reserves.
</TEXT>
