<SECOND>AM-Pentagon-Egypt,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cheney Meets Egyptian Counterpart</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney met for the
first time on Monday with Egyptian Defense Minister Youssef Sabry
Abu-Taleb and reported afterward they had established ``a sound
working relationship.''
   Cheney, who took over the Pentagon earlier this spring, pledged
to meet regularly and to work closely with his counterpart, who was
named to his post in April.
   The Pentagon chief added that he intends to visit Egypt early
next year.
   ``I believe we've established a sound working relationship as
well as a close personal friendship,'' Cheney said in remarks
before reporters.
   ``It is well known that Egypt has long been an influential voice
for moderation in the Middle East and an advocate for a just and
lasting peace in the region. A militarily strong, politically
stable Egypt is critical to our efforts in the search for this
elusive peace,'' Cheney said.
   In a move that caught many off guard, Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak named Abu-Taleb defense minister and commander-in-chief of
the armed forces last April, replacing Field Marshal Abdel-Halim
Abu-Ghazala, who had been in office for more than eight years.
   The main purpose of Abu-Taleb's visit to the United States, the
first since he was appointed defense minister, was to get
acquainted with key Bush administration officials.
   Abu-Taleb said the talks were conducted ``in a spirit of
cooperation and commitment. It has reassured me that we are both
dedicated to keeping our relationship strong and thriving.''
   The Egyptian official, asked about the talks, said they touched
on the coproduction of the Abrams M-1A1 tank, among other matters.
