<FIRST>r i AM-France-GuardianAngels     08-07 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Guardian Angels,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guardian Angels Patrol Paris Metro</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York-based Guardian Angels scouted the
Paris Metro in their red berets and white T-shirts Monday to see
whether they should begin anti-crime subway patrols despite
official opposition.
   Lisa Sliwa, co-leader of the group with her husband Curtis, told
reporters she and three Guardian Angels from London would spend the
week traveling the Paris subways ``to see if we're needed.''
   ``The situation is not as bad in Paris as in New York. Here it's
possible to take preventive action to keep things from getting
worse,'' Mrs. Sliwa said, speaking in French at a news conference
at the busy Chatelet Metro stop in the heart of the city.
   She said she was disappointed that officials in Mayor Jacques
Chirac's office and in the Paris transit authority did not respond
to her requests for meetings.
   ``I want at least a chance to explain what we're doing,'' she
said. ``Afterwards, they can be against it. But if Parisians want
us to be here, we'll stay.''
   The transit authority later issued a statement saying, ``We are
completely opposed to those who act as a militia or other police
force.''
   It noted, however, that any citizen has the right ``to intervene
... when there is danger.'' The statement noted that, under a plan
announced in June, subway security was reinforced and a controller
named to coordinate police efforts in the metro.
   The Guardian Angeles, created in New York in 1979, have
patrolled the London Underground since May.
</TEXT>
