<FIRST>r i AM-EastGermans     08-07 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East Germans,0677</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Germans Leave Austria for West Germany</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 150 of the hundreds of East Germans
who have fled their communist homeland through Hungary to Austria
left Monday for West Germany and a new life.
   The East Germans, most in their early 20s and carrying papers
provided by the West German Embassy in Vienna, boarded one of the
trains that leave each night with refugees bound for West Germany.
   Embassy spokesmen will not say how many East Germans have passed
through Vienna since May, when Hungary's communist regime began
dismantling barbed wire fences and fortifications along its border
with Austria.
   Officials in Budapest, Hungary, caused a stir last week in the
Soviet bloc by saying they might offer asylum to East Germans who
can prove political persecution. A Budapest official said Monday
border police had stopped putting special stamps on the passports
of East Germans caught trying to cross the border.
   Austrian authorities said they had registered at least 400 East
German refugees before West Germany asked them last Friday to stop
making the figures public. They said the true figure could be at
least six times that because many of the East Germans do not report
to police.
   In Bonn, Ottfried Hennig, parliamentary state secretary for the
Ministry of Inter-German Relations, said West Germany feared East
Germany might impose new travel restrictions to stop the refugees.
   Western news reports say say about 200 East Germans are inside
the West German embassy in Budapest. The official East German news
agency ADN said Monday letting the refugees stay there was ``gross
interference'' in East Germany's internal affairs.
   About 100,000 East Germans are expected to make their way West
this year because of the lack of reform at home.
   Three groups of young East Berliners who recently followed
different routes across the border sat in Vienna's Westbahnhof
railroad station Monday and told escape stories ranging from
harrowing to casual.
   All cited the lack of personal freedom as the main reason for
leaving home. They also said their parents knew of their decision
and supported them.
   ``You can have a pile of money, but if you want to buy something
decent, you can't spend it,'' said one young man who had worked in
a restaurant. ``You run around the shops looking for a T-shirt,
just a T-shirt, and you run out with tears in your eyes. We want to
breathe.''
   Like many other East Germans who spoke with reporters, he asked
not to be identified, fearing his comments might cause trouble for
relatives and friends.
   Joerg, 21, made it across from Hungary on the second try, with a
friend, ``but I wouldn't recommend our route to anyone.'' He showed
scars left on his arm by barbed wire and thorns.
   Hungary says it has dismantled fortifications along about half
the 160-mile frontier with Austria. On their escape Thursday night,
Joerg said he and his friend got caught in the part still standing.
   ``We ran for about two hours, then we must have hit a trip wire,
which set off two flares shooting into the air,'' he said.
   After that they thought they heard warning shots. They bumped
into barbed wire, stayed low because of dogs, vehicles and voices,
and then ran several miles, Joerg said.
   Some who made it to safety only on the second or third try
praised the Hungarians.
   ``The first time, we were standing in a wood and the border
guard saw us,'' Joerg said. ``He was so nice, about my age. I gave
him a cigarette, a tissue because he had a cold. ... He was like my
brother.''
   But the Hungarian reported the incident and the two East Germans
were taken to a barracks where men in plainclothes threatened to
stamp their passports and ordered them out of the border zone.
   Joerg said, however, that ``one of the soldiers virtually told
me where to try again.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
