<FIRST>u i AM-CentralAmerica 2dLd-Writethru a0640 08-07 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Central America, 2d Ld - Writethru, a0640,0692</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Presidents Agree on Plan to Disband Contras</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 15 grafs, agreement reached. Picks up 14th pvs `In
exchange'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN WRIGHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TELA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five Central American presidents announced
agreement Monday on a plan for demobilizing 11,000 Nicaraguan
rebels based in the mountains of Honduras.
   President Jose Azcona of Honduras said the plan calls for the
rebels, known as Contras, to surrender their arms to a force of
Spanish, West German and Canadian soldiers. He said the agreement
sets a 90-day timetable for demobilization and repatriation of the
Contras.
   ``The accord asks the international community for support,''
said Azcona, who read the text of a communique.
   The agreement also calls for negotiations to achieve a peace
accord in El Salvadoor between the government and leftist
guerrillas of the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front.
   The accord was signed at the end of a three-day summit attended
by the presidents of Nicaragua, Honduras, El Salvador, Costa Rica
and Guatemala.
   Earlier in the day, President Daniel Ortega of Nicaragua told
reporters: ``The United States is exerting great pressure so no
agreement is reached. They are in direct contact with all the
delegations except Nicaragua.''
   Salvadoran President Alfredo Cristiani denied that. ``We have
not received any pressure,'' he said.
   The presidents had said they would announce a timetable Monday
on resettling the Contras. Monday was the third day of their meting.
   Talks had appeared deadlocked earlier in the day and President
Vinicio Cerezo of Guatemala said the leaders were wrestling with
tough issues.
   ``We're discussing the most difficult points so far. There has
been an attitude of goodwill, flexibility and a disposition to
resolve things,'' he said.
   Oscar Arias, president of Costa Rica, also denied pressure from
Washington.
   Arias, who won the Nobel Peace Prize for writing a peace
agreement and promoting dialogue, said, ``I'm very content. I'm
very optimistic.''
   Copies of a bilateral agreement between Honduras and Nicaragua
calling for withdrawal of the Contras from Honduras by Dec. 6 were
distributed to reporters earlier Monday. Jose Leon Talavera,
Nicaragua's deputy foreign minister, said it would be part of the
final accord.
   In exchange, Nicaragua is to drop its case against Honduras at
the World Court in the Hague. Nicaragua accuses Honduras of
allowing the Contras to operate from that country.
   ``There are some sticking points with respect to all the
issues,'' said Honduran Foreign Minister Carlos Lopez Contreras.
``So we'll have to see if we can get a fresh review of them.''
   The presidents agreed at a February meeting in El Salvador to
dismantle the Nicaraguan rebels, but delayed a decision on the
mechanics and timetable until this meeting.
   Ortega gave the other presidents a letter from the Salvadoran
rebels asking their cooperation in negotiating an end to the
9-year-old civil war.
   Cristiani said his government was willing to negotiate with the
rebels, on condition that ``once the talks begin that they not look
for excuses to break them.''
   The Bush administration has been lobbying Central American
governments to keep the U.S.-backed Contras active until February's
scheduled elections in Nicaragua.
   The U.S. government had four observers at the meeting but they
were meeting delegates outside the talks, not attending the
sessions.
   Ortega signed an agreement Friday with the domestic political
opposition, which calls for demobilizing the Contras in Honduran
camps. In exchange, he has pledged democratic reforms.
   The bilateral plan calls for resettling the 11,000 Contras and
12,000 dependents, who are living in Honduras along the Nicaraguan
border.
   Fighting has been reduced to sporadic clashes since last year,
when the United States cut off military aid and the two sides
reached a temporary truce. Since then, both sides have said they
would not carry out offensive operations.
   The Contras have been fighting the leftist Sandinistas since
1981, alleging the government betrayed the goals of the 1979
revolution that ousted dictator Anastasio Somoza in 1979.
   El Salvador's civil war has left 70,000 dead, while 50,000
people have been killed in Nicaragua's conflict.
</TEXT>
