<FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-89 1911EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Contras     08-07 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Contras,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defiant Despite Circumstances, Rebels Have Few Choices</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Central America</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S.-backed Contra rebels
fighting Nicaragua's Sandinista government on Monday reiterated
their defiance of the opposition arrayed against them in Central
America.
   ``We will not lay down our arms and our fight will continue in
the mountains of Nicaragua,'' said Boanerges Mathus of the Contra
general staff.
   As he spoke, the five Central American presidents were meeting
in Tela, Honduras about the rebels' future, with the goal of
disbanding the Contras.
   Adolfo Calero, a Contra political leader, said he would not ask
the men to lay down their arms until after the Nicaraguan elections
in February. The United Statrs has said it wants the rebel force to
remain intact until then.
   ``We're ready to exchange arms for democracy, but not for
promises,'' Calero said in a speech Monday in Madison, Ala.
   The Contras have been fighting the Sandinistas since 1981 and
about 50,000 people have been killed. They say the leftist
Sandinista government betrayed the 1979 revolution that ousted
dictator Anastasio Somoza.
   Fighting has declined sharply since February 1988, when the
United States cut off military aid to the Contras, limiting
assistance to humanitarian aid.
   At a February summit, the presidents agreed the Contras would be
resettled in exchange for free elections in Nicaragua. President
Daniel Ortega's government has scheduled the vote but the matter of
disbanding the Contras has not been settled.
   Although the Sandinistas and the Contras agreed March 21 to
suspend offensive operations, talks aimed at a permanent end to the
7-year-old war are at an impasse and the rebels continue to launch
sporadic attacks.
   U.S. officials say the resistance has ``frayed somewhat around
the edges'' since the cease-fire, but that the Contras have
maintained high morale.
   ``If the presidents of Guatemala, El Salvador, Honduras,
Nicaragua and Costa Rica agree to bury us, we will abandon Honduran
territory and fight from the mountains of Nicaragua,'' said Mathus.
``We will seek economic and military support from other Western
nations if the United States suspends aid.''
   Although the leadership is a cultured elite based in Miami and
includes former leaders of Somoza's hated National Guard, most
Contras are former sharecroppers or rural businessmen.
   About 11,000 Contra fighters and 12,000 dependents have moved
from Nicaragua into Honduran border camps.
   Many fled Nicaragua because the Sandinista government was
forcing them to sell crops at low prices and join rural
co-operatives. Others fled the draft, not wanting to fight for the
Sandinistas, and ended up fighting against them.
   Many have begun to farm or to work on coffee plantations in
Honduras, but the Hondurans have made it difficult for most Contras
to get work permits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
