<FIRST>r i AM-Burma-Turmoil     08-07 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burma-Turmoil,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Begin Hunger Strike to Commemorate Uprising</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seventy-two members of the leading
opposition party began a two-day fast in Burma's capital on Monday
in remembrance of pro-democracy demonstrators killed in an army
crackdown a year ago, a Western diplomat said.
   On Aug. 8, 1988, tens of thousands of Burmese in Rangoon joined
a protest against 25 years of authoritarian rule in Burma. The next
day, soldiers shot dead hundreds of demonstrators.
   Nationwide unrest continued but was crushed after Gen. Saw Maung
seized power on Sept. 18. His troops killed hundreds more and
imposed martial law.
   The diplomat, reached by telephone from Bangkok, said the 72
members of the National League for Democracy were fasting in the
party's office in Rangoon.
   They also were demanding the release of political prisoners, he
said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   He described the protest as ``feeble'' compared to those held
before July 20, when authorities arrested two party leaders and
began hauling in hundreds of party members.
   Party Secretary-General Aung San Suu Kyi has been reported on a
hunger strike but no details have emerged.
   ``I don't doubt that she started it (the hunger strike), but I
am rather doubtful that she is still on it,'' the diplomat said.
</TEXT>
