<FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-89 1924EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Abortion-California     08-07 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion-California,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abortion Issue Plays Key Role In California Assembly Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ESCONDIDO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An obscure California legislative
district has become a political battleground in which the U.S.
Supreme Court's recent decision on abortion is playing a crucial
role.
   Voters go to the polls Tuesday in a race both pro-choice and
anti-abortion activists say marks the first legislative election in
the nation since the high court's July 3 ruling gave states more
authority to restrict abortions.
   Voters will choose a representative for the 76th Assembly
District from among eight candidates. The winner will succeed GOP
Assemblyman Bill Bradley, who died June 1.
   The special election would normally excite little outside
interest. But the abortion issue has made a difference.
   ``It's not the sole reason I'm going to choose someone, but it
will definitely be a consideration,'' said Escondido resident Troy
Gagielo, who said he was ``definitely looking for a pro-choice
candidate.''
   Six Republicans and two Democrats are stumping the sweltering
streets and rural ranches, and the campaigning has been lively,
despite the difficulties of summer apathy, the short time period
and a huge district.
   The mushroom-shaped 76th Assembly District has 65,439 voters and
is overwhelmingly Republican _ 54.2 percent to 32.7 percent
Democrat.
   Only one of the six Republicans, the president of the state
Board of Registered Nursing, is openly pro-choice and supports
state funding of abortions for poor women.
   ``Health care is the issue to me,'' said Tricia Hunter, 36, of
Bonita, a registered nurse who is also director of surgical
services at Chula Vista Community Hospital. ``You cannot restrict
health care because of individual beliefs.''
   Hunter says the abortion issue is going to play a big part in
the election. ``It has definitely spurred interest in the race
throughout the state,'' she said.
   Both Democrats are also pro-choice. Three of the Republicans are
strongly opposed to abortion.
   The two other Republican candidates, Deputy Mayor Linda Brannon,
42, of Poway and Dennis Koolhaas, 34, of Escondido, say only that
they oppose state funding of abortion. But abortion should not be a
major issue in the race, they insist.
   ``This is not a campaign that should be a one-issue race,'' said
Koolhaas.
   All the candidates see crime, education and
growth-transportation as among the biggest issues in the district.
   The special election process is an odd one. All candidates will
be on the ballot together, regardless of party. Voters will get one
ballot and can vote for whomever they choose. If one candidate gets
more than 50 percent of the vote _ unlikely in such a split field _
he or she is elected to the office. If that does not happen, the
top Republican and the top Democrat will face each other in a
runoff election on Oct. 3.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
