<FIRST>r w AM-Scam-Alabama     08-07 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scam-Alabama,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Church Treasurer Bilks Investors of $18 Million</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Ungodly Scams,Bjt,a0542; also on financial wire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alabama securities investigators leaving the
home of church deacon Steven Streit after interviewing him about
possible fraud found on his doorstep a $35,000 check from a
would-be investor.
   ``These people were begging to invest with him,'' said Robert
Rash, director of the Alabama Securities Commission.
   Streit is now serving a 10-year prison sentence for fraud for
running a con game that bilked nearly 200 people out of an
estimated $18 million.
   Streit's investment scam was among several cited by state
securities regulators Monday at a news conference announcing a
15-state survey of religious-oriented investment schemes that have
cost 15,000 investors some $450 million since 1985.
   U.S. Rep. William Dickinson, R-Ala., was among the investors
taken in by Streit, the former treasurer of one of the largest
Baptist churches in Alabama.
   ``He never invested any of the money,'' said Rash.
   Streit, who kept a stock market ticker running in his office and
maintained three satellite dishes at his $400,000 house, told
investors he had a direct link to every major exchange in the
world, said Rash.
   Although Streit promised an exhorbitant return of 30 percent to
35 percent per month, his investors didn't question him. One victim
stated, ``It was sort of comforting to see the Bible verse printed
at the end of the monthly statements.''
   Streit traded on his role as a deacon of the church as well as a
former accountant and bank trust officer to bilk ``virtually every
prominent businessman in the Huntsville area,'' said Rash.
   ``Everybody thought he had divine guidance, he played his role
real well,'' Rash said in an interview.
   Dickinson was out of the country and was unavailable for comment.
</TEXT>
