<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-Prostitutes     08-07 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Prostitutes,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chihuahua Prostitutes Demand a Red Light District</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spokesman for the Chihuahua state
government said Monday it is willing to discuss with prostitutes
and bar owners the opening of a ``tolerance zone'' in which
prostitution would be allowed.
   But spokesman Alfonso Sanchez Gallo said: ``First they would
have to find an appropriate place and then they would have to get
the funds. The bar owners themselves would have to pay for it.''
   Sanchez said prostitutes were meeting with government officials
to discuss the opening of a red light district.
   Last week authorities in Chihuahua City, the state capital,
closed about 31 downtown bars and restaurants they said had become
fronts for prostitution.
   They said the businesses will stay shut despite prostitutes'
threats to strip in protest in front of the capitol building.
   About 1,500 prostitutes threatened to march on the capitol
Monday and undress publicly to press for creation of a red light
district in the city.
   ``There was no march and nobody took off their clothes,''
Sanchez said in a telephone interview.
   He quoted Chihuahua Gov. Fernando Baeza as saying that any bar
or restaurant catering to prostitution would have its license
revoked.
   The Mexico City newspaper Excelsior on Sunday quoted Magdalena
Aguirre, a spokewoman for the prostitutes, as saying she and the
other prostitutes would exhibit themselves ``completely naked'' at
the capitol if their demands were not met.
   Ms. Aguirre ridiculed Baeza's suggestion that prostitutes seek
factory jobs, according to the Sunday edition of the Mexico City
daily La Jornada.
   She was quoted as saying that factories ``only pay 60,000 pesos
($23) a week. We make that much or more in two hours.''
   Sanchez said Baeza had warned the women that it would be illegal
for them to disrobe in public.
   ``The state government has to put the brakes on prostitution. It
isn't legal here,'' the spokesman added.
   Sanchez then mentioned a possible ``tolerance zone.''
   Although prostitution is illegal in Mexico, many city and state
governments have allowed red light districts to operate.
</TEXT>
