<FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-89 2006EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-CivilRights 1stLd-Writethru   08-07 1041</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Civil Rights, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0685,980</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush's Civil Rights Record Spotty, Civil Rights Advocates Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS grafs 11-12 bgng: ``Bush himself,'' with Bush remarks
to Florida meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush promised to deal with the
problems of poverty and racial intolerence in his presidency and
his aides claim progress in six months in office, but civil rights
advocates gathered here say his record so far has been spotty.
   Bush's choice of William Lucas to be the Justice Department's
top civil rights enforcer, his refusal to speak out on recent
Supreme Court rulings limiting affirmative action programs and the
dispute with Congress over a new minimum wage are cited most
frequently by his critics.
   Administration aides defend Bush's civil rights commitment,
claiming it is a strong one that dates back to his support of open
housing legislation as a first-term House member in 1968 _ in a
dramatic break with the rest of the Texas delegation.
   And Fred McClure, the highest-ranking black member of the White
House staff, said most of the agenda of the civil rights movement
is ``George Bush's agenda.''
   The president on Tuesday will address the 79th annual Urban
League Conference, whose theme this year is ``Total parity by the
year 2000.''
   Urban League President John E. Jacob is challenging Bush to use
the speech ``to present bold new initiatives that help America's
poor people and put us back on the path of racial progress.''
   White House aides said they do not expect the speech to break
any new ground, despite Jacob' appeal.
   Bush, according to deputy press secretary Stephen Hart, will use
the speech to ``say that we've come a long way but we've got a long
way to go'' on ending discrimination.
   ``It focuses on education as the key to equality. It talks about
education and about drugs,'' said Hart.
   However, the president for some time reportedly has been
considering making a trip to Africa this fall, according to White
House officials. Tuesday's speech might present a good forum for
Bush to announce such a trip.
   Bush himself, in a Monday evening telephone address to a town
meeting sponsored by the Urban League and the NAACP at the Mt.
Olive Baptist Church in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., said he would offer
a ``message of challenge and hope'' in his speech to the Urban
League.
   In his phone talk, he focused on the war against drugs, citing
statistics showing the number of Americans who are frequent cocaine
users was up sharply. ``We're talking addiction,'' Bush said.
``This is an issue we should fight every day.''
   Civil rights leaders appear willing to give Bush some benefit of
doubt on his agenda, partly because he has reached out toward them
from the early days of his presidency. But they suggest his words
don't live up to his deeds.
   ``The civil rights community would give the president high marks
for accessibility and symbolism and rhetoric but low marks on
substantive civil rights policy,'' said Ralph Neas, executive
director of the Leadership Conference on Civil Rights.
   ``So far, the Bush administration has compiled a disappointing
record on civil rights,'' Neas said in an interview.
   Civil rights advocates list these developments as the major
irritants:
   _The Senate debacle over Lucas, a black Detroit lawyer Bush
nominated to head the civil rights division at Justice. Lucas was
widely criticized by black leaders for lacking experience in
discrimination cases and was rejected by the Senate Judiciary
Committee on a 7-7 tie vote.
   Still, the administration continues to stand by the nomination,
including a behind-the-scenes effort by Bush last Friday to get the
full Senate to ignore the committee vote and bring the nomination
to the floor.
   _The administration's refusal to speak out against _ or support
legislation to sidestep _ a series of Supreme Court rulings last
spring that sharply restricted affirmative action and made it more
difficult to prove discrimination in the workplace.
   _Bush's veto of a new minimum wage bill.
   _The president's support of a holdover nomination by former
President Reagan of Vaughn Walker, a San Francisco attorney, to a
federal judgeship in California. Walker came under fire for his
membership in a club that excludes women.
   _The Justice Department's decision to undo existing school
desegregation orders in Georgia, and its filing of a lawsuit
challenging a Prince George's County, Md., desegration plan.
   McClure, the Bush White House liaison with members of Congress,
defends Bush's civil rights policy as a continued effort ``to break
down barriers.''
   At the same time, McClure said, ``You haven't had issues like
civil rights acts, the voting rights act, traditional types of
civil rights measures'' thus far in Bush's adminstration.
   However, McClure said the bipartisan agreement reached last week
with the White House on legislation to extend equal opportunity
protection to Americans with disabilities should be viewed as a key
civil-rights move on Bush's part.
   Civil rights leaders agreed, giving Bush high marks for his role
in crafting the legislation.
   Jacob, the Urban League president, says that despite major
differences with the administration on some civil rights issues, he
remains hopeful that remaining problems can be worked out ``with
honesty and candor.''
   And Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole, appearing at the Urban
League conference Monday, touted administration planning grants to
12 cities and rural areas for getting ``at-risk youths'' into the
economic mainstream.
   She said stamping discrimination ``out of our economy'' remains
a high priority of the administration.
   And Bush, addressing a ceremony honoring the 25th anniversary of
the passage of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, told a White House
audience last month he would be satisfied ``with nothing less than
equality of opportunity for all Americans.''
   ``The hard lesson of the passing years is that it has not been
enough to wage a war against the old forms of bigotry and
inequality,'' Bush added.
   But Rep. William Gray, D-Pa., majority whip of the House,
scoffed on Monday at Bush's notion of a ``kinder and gentler
nation.''
   He told the Urban League forum: ``It does none of us any good to
talk about the benefits of economic growth and opportunity and yet
not acknowledge that there has been stagnation and a worsening of
conditions for some Americans, and especially African-Americans.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
