<FIRST>r a AM-FiresRdp     08-07 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fires Rdp,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Lightning Strikes Across Northwest Forests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER PETTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms with lightning but no rain raised a threat of more
fires Monday across the dry forests of northern California and
moved toward western and central Idaho, where flames have already
charred 105,000 acres.
   ``That's a bad sign if it's coming this way,'' said George
Bukenhofer of the Payette National Forest in Idaho. ``We don't need
any more of this. We have lots of active fire already.''
   The Boise Interagency Fire Center, the national fire
coordination center, said 23,000 firefighters were battling the
worst of the fires on 182,000 acres, primarily in Idaho, Oregon and
California. The center said the war has already cost over $27
million.
   More than 220,000 acres have been charred in a bout of mostly
lightning-caused fires that began July 26.
   More than 3,000 lightning strikes were reported overnight in
Oregon, Washington, Nevada, California and Idaho.
   ``A lot of these strikes will hit a tree or the ground,'' said
Forest Service spokesman Mike Ferris in Oregon. ``They're what we
call a sleeper. They'll smolder (for days) and a little wind will
come behind them and all of a sudden they'll burn.''
   Before the lightning strikes, eastern Oregon firefighters had
consolidated gains made during cool weather last week and predicted
that many of the 100 fires that had burned 82,000 acres would be
contained by midweek.
   Airplanes sent over national forests Monday in Washington to
look for telltale smoke found dozens of lightning-caused spot
fires, most of which were quickly contained by ground crews.
   Hardest hit were the Wenatchee and Okanogan national forests,
where crews fought 16 lightning-caused spot fires, none of which
grew to more than one-half acre, said Sheela McLean, an Okanogan
Forest spokeswoman.
   Hundreds of Army soldiers moved through the Interagency Fire
Center for training and eventual deployment to the firelines as
land managers pressed for more manpower.
   ``In past years, we've used the military for mop-up, but that's
not happening this time,`` said Boise National Forest spokeswoman
Pat Irwin in Idaho. ``They're being used as mop-up for a few days,
but that's just their training. The incident commanders believe
they can be as good as class-one hot-shot crews because they're
disciplined, used to working together and they're physically fit.''
   In hardest-hit Idaho, more than 9,000 people were committed to
the major fires, like the 42,000-acre Lowman Complex of fires that
destroyed a small resort town 70 miles northeast of Boise.
   Major gains were made during cooler weather that persisted into
the weekend, but the mercury rose again Monday and humidity was
declining.
   Firefighters in southern and central California reported
progress Monday on two blazes that have blackened thousands of
acres of forest and wilderness.
   The 7,550-acre Balch Camp Fire in the Sierra foothills east of
Fresno was 95 percent surrounded, officials said.
   The Vail Fire in the Cleveland National Forest east of San
Diego, which was ignited by a target shooter's bullet nine days
ago, was 90 percent contained, said U.S. Forest Service spokeswoman
Jean Magarrell. The fire had torched a house and trailer and
threatened the historic Mount Palomar Observatory and the Eagle
Crag nature sanctuary earlier in the week.
   Near Coalville, Utah, about 45 miles east of Salt Lake City,
firefighters were close to containing the 1,700-acre Chalk Creek
blaze.
   In northwestern Nebraska, a fire that blackened 3,000 acres of
brush and timber in canyon country near Belmont was largely
contained but control wasn't expected for two to three days.
</TEXT>
