<FIRST>r a AM-GangSentence     08-07 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gang Sentence,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Sentences Men for Gang-related Killing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men convicted of killing a teen-ager
they mistakenly believed had given the hand signal of a rival
street gang were each sentenced Monday to 41 years in prison.
   The sentences for Gregory T. Smith, 18, and Darrell J. Massey,
19, exceeded both the state sentencing guidelines of 26 to 34 years
and the prosecutor's recommendations.
   ``Their crime is unique in its enormity,'' said Pierce County
Superior Court Judge D. Gary Steiner.
   Smith and Massey were convicted July 5 of first-degree murder in
the shooting death of Brenda J. Harris, 17. They also were
convicted of two counts each of attempted murder of the other
occupants of the car in which the girl was riding. The other
occupants were not injured.
   Ms. Harris, who had no known gang ties, and her friends were
riding through east Tacoma on March 24 when she waved at someone
she thought she recognized.
   Police said Smith, Massey and two other men associated with the
Crips street gang then pursued the vehicle and opened fire on it.
Ms. Harris was struck in the head by a rifle bullet.
   The other men in the car with Massey and Smith testified against
them and pleaded guilty to lesser charges.
   Nancy Harris, Ms. Harris' mother, held a photograph of her
daughter and wept throughout the sentencing. The prison terms
weren't long enough, she said, adding, ``It's not going to bring my
daughter back.''
</TEXT>
