<FIRST>u w AM-Leland-Plane 4thLd-Writethru   08-07 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Leland-Plane, 4th Ld-Writethru,a0696,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rep. Leland's Plane Missing in Africa</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 3rd graf: ``In Addis,'' with embassy quote; INSERTS
graf 6: ``That would,'' to give second count; SUBS graf 6 pvs, now graf
8: ``Shub said,'' to locate the camp.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plane carrying Rep. Mickey Leland, D-Texas,
congressional aides and several other people failed to arrive as
expected at a refugee camp near the Ethiopian-Sudanese border
Monday, the State Department said.
   ``We are concerned about the welfare of Mr. Leland and his
group,'' department spokesman Adam Shub said in a statement. Leland
aides suggested the group simply got behind schedule and was
staying overnight in another camp.
   In Addis Ababa, the Ethiopian capital, John Guerra, a political
and economics office at the U.S. Embassy, said in a telephone
interview with The Associated Press in Nairobi: ``We don't know
anything for sure yet. We are hoping they got into problems with
the weather and diverted somewhere.''
   There were conflicting accounts of who was aboard the plane.
   A Leland spokeswoman said the congressman was accompanied by two
aides and three officials from relief organizations. A source on
Capitol Hill, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the party
included three congressional staffers, a friend of Leland's, three
officials from the U.S. Embassy, one embassy spouse, an Ethiopian
employee of the embassy and two Ethiopian government officials. Two
of the Americans worked for the Agency for International
Development, he said.
   That would make 12 people in the party. Guerra said the plane
was carrying 14 people. It was not clear whether that included the
Ethipoian pilot and co-pilot.
   The plane is owned by Ethiopia's Relief and Rehabilitation
Commission, the government's welfare agency.
   Shub said the plane left Addis Ababa, at 10:40 a.m. local time,
headed for the refugee camp, Fugnido, about 300 miles to the
southwest. The plane did not arrive at the camp, and it did not
return to Addis Ababa as expected at 5 p.m. local time, 10 a.m. EDT
Monday in the United States, he said.
   Greta Morris, a department spokeswoman, said she did not expect
that search planes would be dispatched from Addis Ababa until
daybreak. ``We're working closely with the Ethiopians,'' she said.
   Leland is chairman of the House Select Committee on Hunger. He
has taken a keen interest in Africa's refugees, and visited the
same area in March, officials said.
   The camp the group had been headed for is run by the United
Nations High Commission for Refugees. It is home to about thousands
of refugees who have fled civil war in neighboring Sudan.
   The plane's takeoff Monday morning was delayed about two hours
because of bad weather, officials said.
   Planes must fly over rugged terrain to reach the refugee camp,
but the aircraft would not pass over the area where rebels are
battling Ethiopia's government. Ethiopia's separatist movements are
based in the northern part of the country in the Horn of Africa.
   ``We think it's very premature to be concerned at this point,''
said Timmie Jensen, a spokeswoman for the House Select Committee on
Hunger, which Leland heads.
   ``This kind of thing comes up when you're in the bush,'' she
said.
   Alma Newsom, another Leland spokeswoman, said, ``For all
practical purposes, they're cut off. They're going to be overdue
all night. They're going to be overnight in the camp.''
   ``My guess is once en route, the camp that was the original
destination was too far and they opted to go to a different camp,''
Ms. Newsom said. ``Even at that, once they got on the ground and
began their tour, they simply ran out of time to end their tour and
get back.''
   She said pilots were very strict about adhering to a 5 p.m.
curfew to return to Addis Ababa.
</TEXT>
