<FIRST>r a AM-StateLegislatures     08-07 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-State Legislatures,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>Medicaid, Prison Spending Grow, But State Budgets Are Healthy, Report
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State spending on prisons and health care
continued to climb and eat into education budgets in 1989, but most
states are financially healthy, according to a report released
Monday at a national meeting of legislators.
   The report by the fiscal staff of National Conference of State
Legislatures showed that education, though considered the No. 1
issue across the country, did not fare much better in spending than
other areas in most states.
   More than 5,000 people, mainly legislators and state officials
and staff, are expected to attend the weeklong convention.
   The overall increase in spending in state budgets was 7.2
percent _ up from 6.6 percent a year ago.
   Spending on corrections _ principally for prison capital needs
and operations _ rose by 14.1 percent among the states as a whole,
while the increase in Medicaid costs was 10.4 percent.
   Elementary-secondary education spending rose by 7.8 percent, and
funding for colleges and universities jumped 7.3 percent.
   Education makes up more than 50 percent of state budgets across
the country.
   West Virginia, which had to pour money into teacher retirement
and health insurance, had the largest increase in education funding
with 25.7 percent.
   Next were Illinois with a 17.7 percent increase, Nevada and New
Hampshire with 16.8 percent, Ohio with 15.2 percent and Georgia
with 14.7 percent.
   The report, however, showed that states have an estimated $10.9
billion in reserves _ or 4.4 percent of states' general funds.
That's the highest amount of reserve fund balances in nine years.
   Steven Gold, director of fiscal affairs for the NCSL, said most
states are ``comfortable'' from a financial standpoint. But, Gold
said, ``the margin that is protecting them from being uncomfortable
is not so large.''
   Louisiana Senate President Pro Tempore Samuel Nunez Jr., NCSL
president, said experience has shown that financial conditions
among states can change rapidly and often are tied to the national
economy.
   ``The greatest concentration of fiscal problems this year was in
the New England states and in New York and New Jersey, places that
just two years ago were faring better than most states.''
   Nunez also pointed out that 1989 was ``an active year for state
tax policy,'' with tax increases totaling $3.5 billion in 30 states.
   In 1980, states had reserve fund balances totaling $11.8
million. Lee Daniels, NCSL president-elect and minority leader of
the Illinois House, noted that two years later ``many states were
in severe difficulty as they felt the effects of a national
recession.''
   ``The current fiscal health is certainly not a cause for
complacency,'' Daniels said.
   Increased spending on prisons comes at a time of declining crime
in many areas. Gold tied the cause to court-ordered prison
improvements and tougher sentencing guidelines.
   Nunez said the economic future of states is clouded by large
trade and federal budget deficits and about what will happen to
federal aid and federal mandates on various programs.
   He said unfunded federal mandates have added billions of dollars
in new responsibilities to the states in recent years.
   Federal initiatives in welfare reform, catastrophic health care
and nursing home legislation will raise state costs by more than $2
billion per year, Nunez said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
