<DOCNO> AP890807-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-89 2151EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Baker-Mexico 2ndLd-Writethru a0665 08-07 0803</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baker-Mexico, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0665,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker, Brady Hail Mexican Policies, See Bright Economic Future</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS new grafs 10-12 with Baker, Solana comments after discussion;
picks up ``We want, 12th graf pvs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III said
Monday that Mexico, after years of stagnation, has become an
economic model for other debtor nations because of the ``bold,
far-sighted policies'' of President Carlos Salinas de Gortari.
   He also said that Mexico's record over the past six months in
cracking down on drug trafficking has made clear the government's
commitment that ``it wants to tear the roots of the opium poppy and
marijuana plant from its soil.''
   Baker spoke at the ceremonial opening of daylong talks that
featured the presence of an unusually large array of senior Bush
administration officials. With Baker were 40 other officials,
including four Cabinet members.
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady set the tone for the
discussions, telling a morning news conference that ``great
progress has been made in economic and financial fields that are
important to our two countries.''
   Brady hailed the debt agreement Mexico reached with commercial
banks two weeks ago that provides for, among other things, a
reduction in Mexico's debt servicing obligations. Payments on the
country's $107 billion foreign debt have contributed to a sharp
decline in living standards over the past seven years.
   Brady said that Mexico has taken steps to make the business
climate here more favorable for foreign investment and to lower
barriers to trade. Tax reform and deregulation also will help
stimulate economic growth, he said.
   Later, Baker, standing before the assembled delegations at a
Foreign Ministry conference room for the opening ceremony, said:
``The United States has no more important relationship than with
its neighbor and friend, the Republic of Mexico. These are not mere
words _ they represent the solemn commitment of the United States.''
   Expanding on Brady's comments about Mexico's economic policies,
Baker said Mexico's ``bold, far-sighted'' approach has convinced
the private banks and international lending institutions that
``Mexico is worthy of credit and trust.''
   ``We believe that Mexico can once again set an example that
other nations can follow,'' Baker said. At his news conference,
Brady expressed hope that similar debt reduction agreements can be
reached with the Philippines, Venezuela, Costa Rica and Morocco.
   Afterwards, Baker praised the talks as ``very productive and
highly successful.''
   Mexico's Foreign Affairs Minister Fernando Solana was far more
restrained in his remarks. After the meeting, he said the
discussions were carried out ``in an atmosphere of mutual respect''
and were marked by ``intelligent analyses'' of the problems of the
two nations.
   At the opening ceremony, he praised the ``high level of maturity
and cordiality'' between the two countries, but said Mexico will
never surrender its Latin American identity despite its
geographical proximity to the United States.
   ``We want to be evermore good friends of the United States but
never at the cost of affecting the values which determine our
essence and which shape us as a nation,'' he said.
   He said that U.S. foreign investment in Mexico is far less than
what it should be and that the improvement in East-West relations
should lead to an increase in the resources the United States makes
available for development and well-being.
   But based on the remarks of Baker and Brady, U.S. relations with
Mexico have come a long way since the period during the Reagan
administration of mutual recriminations over drug trafficking and
Central America policy.
   Mexico's perceived role as one of the staunchest supporters in
the hemisphere of Nicaragua's leftist government and the rebel
movement in El Salvador embittered officials of the Reagan
administration.
   With the almost simultaneous advent of the Bush and Salinas
admininistrations, Central America has faded as an issue and there
is a sense in Washington that Mexico is far more serious now about
confronting drug smugglers.
   Baker acknowledged that the United States bears part of the
blame for the drug problem because of the ``senseless demand'' for
drugs, a statement that reflects a long-held Mexican view.
   Mexico has been a principal source of heroin and marijuana and a
transit point for U.S.-bound cocaine shipments. Mexican officials
believe a reduction in U.S. demand is the most effective means of
combating the problem.
   Nonetheless, Baker said Salinas has taken decisive action on the
drug issue. ``Mexico's success over the past six months in
capturing and prosecuting drug traffickers has seized the world's
attention.''
   The other Cabinet members who joined Baker and Brady for the
talks, held under the auspices of the U.S.-Mexico Binational
Commission, were Attorney General Dick Thornburgh, Commerce
Secretary Robert Mosbacher and U.S. Trade Representative Carla
Hills.
   Also on the agenda were issues relating to the U.S.-Mexican
border, the environment, fisheries, trade and investment and
cultural ties.
</TEXT>
