<FIRST>r i AM-Suriname-Truce     08-07 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Suriname-Truce,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Agreement With Rebels Approved By National Assembly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARAMARIBO, Suriname (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Assembly on Monday
approved a cease-fire in Suriname's 3-year-old guerrilla war that
was signed by the government and rebels in late July.
   The 51-member assembly deliberated eight hours before voting
44-2 for the cease-fire.
   Prime Minister Henk Arron said disputes with the army over the
terms of the accord had been overcome. He said the truce will be
implemented within the next weeks after the final wording is put
together.
   The Surinamese military, which ruled the country until 1987, had
protested provisions of the agreement that allow the rebels to keep
their weapons and eventually join the South American nation's
police force.
   The government and rebels agreed in principle to the accord on
July 22 at a meeting in French Guiana.
   It was to end the fighting in eastern Suriname between
government forces and the rebels, led by Ronnie Brunswijk, 27, a
former bodyguard to Lt. Col. Desi Bouterse who ruled Suriname from
1980-1987.
   Bouterse was replaced by a civilian government in 1987
elections, but the army still has influence in Surinamese politics
under a state of emergency in large parts of the nation.
   The truce also calls for an end to the state of emergency and
for an aid program for eastern Suriname, where Brunswijk has his
power base.
   The three-year strife, which is seen as a personal feud between
Brunswijk and Bouterse, has cost hundreds of lives.
   Suriname, a nation of 400,000, gained independence from Holland
in 1975.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
