<FIRST>r a AM-StateLegislatures-Abortion     08-07 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-State Legislatures-Abortion,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pro-Choice, Anti-abortion Groups Battle For Legislators' Attention</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Abortion-California, AM-State Legislatures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIL BROYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 600 pro-choice and anti-abortion
demonstrators held competing rallies Monday to gain the attention
of lawmakers attending the National Conference of State
Legislatures.
   Nearly 5,000 delegates are attending the non-partisan group's
six-day annual meeting. Busloads of delegates were confronted by
opposing demonstrations Monday evening.
   The U.S. Supreme Court last month upheld a Missouri law that
placed restrictions on abortions, giving back to states the right
to restrict access to abortions.
   ``We just want to be sure they understand there are a lot of
people in the pro-life majority,'' said Clayton Lewis, director of
the Biblical Action League.
   Across the street, Lesa Kubik, spokeswoman for the Tulsa
Pro-Choice organization, said her group wanted to send a message to
legislators: ``My Lord, if this is happening in Oklahoma, what's
happening in my state?
   ``We're in Oklahoma. We're in the Bible Belt. We're in one of
the most conservative areas of the United States. These are people
who are angry that (the Supreme Court decision) has happened,'' Ms.
Kubik said.
   Observers estimated the groups at 300 people apiece.
   Jerald Larry, a Texas state representative from Dallas, watched
the demonstrations and said it reminded him of the ``lively
debate'' over the issue in Texas last session.
   Bob Price, a state assemblyman from Las Vegas, Nev., watched the
crowd with a smile.
   ``I really like the fact that in America, both sides can point
out their thoughts. It's just wonderful,'' he said.
   ``I'm not looking forward to this when we take it up,'' he
added. ``It's going to be the most contentious issue we've had in a
long time.''
   The lawmakers are to disuss abortion at a session on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
