<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-US     08-07 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-US,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Offers Talks on U.S. Bases in Philippines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Monday it was
ready to begin talks on extending U.S. military bases beyond 1991
and would speed up studies on alternative uses of the facilities if
they are closed.
   National Security Council adviser, Rafael Ileto told reporters,
``We are ready for talks now.'' He said the United States should
propose a date for the beginning of negotiations.
   ``The council examined the security arrangements between the two
countries, particularly the U.S. Military Bases Agreement, which
expires in September 1991,'' Ileto said.
   ``It noted the need for the early resolution of the bases issue
and decided to speed up the completion of plans for the alternative
uses of the U.S. military facilities.''
   The United States maintains six bases in the Philippines,
including Clark Air Base and the Subic Bay Naval Base. They are
among the largest U.S. military garrisons outside the continental
United States.
   Under the Philippine constitution any extension of the bases
must come under a bilateral treaty subject to approval by
two-thirds of the 23-member Senate, where opposition to the
installations is strong.
   President Corazon Aquino has refused to say whether she supports
an extension. In October the United States and the Philippines
reached an agreement allowing the bases to remain until 1991 in
return for $962 million in U.S. military and economic aid over two
years.
   The two countries are expected to begin preliminary talks on a
new treaty later this year. Mrs. Aquino is expected to discuss the
issue when she visits Washington, probably in November.
   About 40,000 American troops, civilian workers and military
dependents are stationed at the facilities.
   Opponents of the bases have suggested the facilities could be
used for commercial ship repair, export processing zones and
industrial parks to soften the economic effects of any U.S. troop
withdrawal.
   On Friday, Singapore's Minister of State for Foreign Affairs,
George Yeo, told parliament that the island nation wanted the
United States to maintain its military presence in the region and
had offered to host some facilities.
   Yeo's statement was seen as an attempt by Singapore to make it
easier for the Manila government to extend the bases agreement. The
Philippines has complained that other non-communist Southeast Asian
nations were unwilling to share the political burden of hosting the
bases.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
