<FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-89 2254EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-Contras-History     08-07 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Contras-History,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Central America</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. financial support, direct or through
proxies, has kept the Nicaraguan resistance movement _ the Contras
_ going since 1981, but at the price of almost endless controversy
between administrations eager to block the consolidation of a
second Marxist-Leninist government in the region and congressional
opponents of intervention.
   Currently, the Bush administration and its Democratic opponents
in Congress are operating under an agreement to provide the Contras
with $49.8 million for food, clothing and other supplies, but no
arms or ammunition, through Feb. 28, 1990, at the rate of $4.5
million a month. The money can be used for resettlement.
   Separately, the Contra leadership in Miami has been receiving a
reported $400,000 a month but that was cut in half in the spring.
Last month the Contra leadership there said it was told to expect
further cuts.
   The agreement between Congress and the administration provides
that the money will stop as of Nov. 30 if Democratic congressional
leaders are not satisfied with the administration's efforts to
support peace.
   The Bush administration had been hoping to keep the Contras
together as a force until after the Nicaraguan elections next
February. Congressional critics have said this effort could be a
violation of their aid agreement with the president.
   The entire Iran-Contra affair revolved around attempts by
elements of the Reagan administration, led by Lt. Col. Oliver North
of the National Security Council staff and CIA Director William
Casey, to divert profits from the secret sale of arms to Iran to
the Contras during a period when Congress had forbidden the use of
U.S. funds.
   As part of that effort, other nations were solicited and some
were ranted aid.
   The House first voted to cut off aid to the Contras in 1983,
after two annual secret appropriations of $19 million each. A later
compromise made $24 million in open aid available to the rebels
that year.
   Another vote to cut off aid came in 1984 after reports that the
CIA had mined Nicaraguan harbors.
   Late in 1984 Congress set aside $14 million but did not release
it, and banned support for paramilitary operations in Nicaragua
without congressional approval.
   An adverse House vote early in 1985 kept the $14 million from
being released although the Senate voted in favor.
   During the summer of 1985 Congress approved $27 million in
``humanitarian'' aid and barred the CIA and the military from any
role in distribution of the funds.
   In the fall of 1986, Congress approved $100 million, a large
part of it for military aid, and lifted restrictions on the CIA.
   Early in 1987, the House tried to hold up the final $40 million
of the $100 million approved the previous year, but the Senate
refused to go along.
   When the 1988 fiscal year began on Sept. 30, 1987, a series of
temporary aid measures began that eventually provided $30 million.
   Early in 1988, Congress killed President Reagan's request for
$36 million in aid, and in March of that year the Contras made a
truce with the Sandinista government. Congress that voted to
provide $48 million, but rejected a request for $47 million in the
summer.
   After he took office, President Bush decided he had no chance of
winning military aid and negotiated his deal with his congressional
critics. A key Bush aide, White House counsel C. Boyden Gray,
suggested in a bizarre episode that the agreement could amount to
an unconstitutional abrogation of the president's powers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
