<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Con artists invoking God's name as endorsement
for investment schemes are working religiously to cheat thousands
of Americans out of hundreds of millions of dollars, state
securities regulators warned Monday.
   In a survey titled ``Preying on the Faithful: The False Prophets
of the Investment World,'' officials said that quick-buck artists
have cheated 15,000 believers out of $450 million since 1985.
   No religious group appears to be more or less susceptible to
fraud. State securities regulators have investigated schemes
preying on black Prtestant churches, Greek Orthodox congregations
and Hispanic Catholic parishes.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Columbia, earthbound for 3{ years
and cannibalized for parts to keep other space shuttles flying, was
pronounced troublefree Monday and ready for a Tuesday morning
launch to put a high-powered spy satellite in orbit.
   The five-man crew was told that the weather appeared to be no
problem for launch. Their ship, the oldest in the fleet, has had
258 modifications to bring it up to par with the others and in the
process gained 2,500 pounds.
   Everything about the mission, except the names of the all-male,
all-military crew, was secret _ including time of liftoff, length
of mission and the cargo in the shuttle's 60-foot-long hold.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MARYVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trial began Monday in a divorce case in
which the judge must decide whether seven frozen embryos should go
to a husband who doesn't want children now or to a wife who cannot
conceive naturally.
   Junior Lewis Davis, 30, in February sued for divorce from Mary
Sue Davis and asked that Mrs. Davis, 28, be barred from ever using
any of the seven fertilized eggs without his consent. Mrs. Davis
contends she should be able to have the eggs implanted without his
consent because it might be her best chance of having a child.
   Blount County Circuit Judge W. Dale Young must decide whether
the embryos deserve consideration as a potential child and
therefore choose who would better serve the interests of a child,
or if the embryos should be considered property and settled as in a
regular property dispute.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TELA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Central American summit bogged down on
Monday _ its final day _ with Nicaragua accusing the United States
of pressuring the region's governments to scuttle the peace process.
   ``The United States is exerting great pressure so no agreement
is reached,'' Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega told reporters.
``They are in direct contact with all the delegations except
Nicaragua.''
   Presidents of five Central American countries had said they
would announce a timetable Monday on resettling the Nicaraguan
Contra rebels, most of whom are now in base camps on the Honduran
side of the border. The presidents huddled for a third day Monday
after reportedly meeting until 4 a.m.
</TEXT>
