<FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-89 0745EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APArts:LondonTheater Adv10   08-07 0801</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: London Theater, Adv 10,0824</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 10</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thurs PMs, Aug 10 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Changing Face of London Hit Shows</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Andrew Lloyd Webber's latest musical ``Aspects of
Love'' is sporting a revised ending and a new song in the second
act even though it only opened in April.
   Peter Shaffer took a fresh look at his comedy hit, ``Lettice and
Lovage,'' and changed endings and the cast changed last fall.
   Increasingly, London shows are evolving during their runs in
ways distinct from both the usual recasting and adjustments that
occur when a show moves to New York or has a long run.
   Directors and writers are having a second look at their work on
home turf. If need be, changes are being made.
   ``The first ending is history,'' Shaffer, the Tony-winning
author of ``Equus'' and ``Amadeus,'' said of ``Lettice and Lovage.''
   The comedy's October 1987 Globe Theater debut finished with the
two stars, Maggie Smith and Margaret Tyzack, plotting to destroy
London's worst buildings with a medieval bronze weapon.
   ``Version one got lots of pleasurable laughs,'' Shaffer, 63,
said in an interview. ``But I suspected once the public got in
their cars, they may have thought, `A pity it went silly in the
end.'''
   Now, instead of two dotty architectural terrorists, the women
imagine themselves tour guides for the ``Eyesore Negation
Detachment,'' leading intrepid visitors around the 50 ugliest
buildings in London.
   ``It gives them a job; it employs what they're good at,'' said
Shaffer. He put in the new ending when Geraldine McEwan and Sara
Kestelman took over the roles last October.
   The play's Broadway bow with the original stars next March will
use the new ending. ``I think it's right now,'' said Shaffer.
``It's better than the original.''
   Shaffer said he would never implement a rewrite until there is a
change of cast or _ as on Broadway _ a fresh staging.
   The creators of ``Aspects'' had no such qualms. No sooner had
the long-awaited musical opened April 17 at the Prince of Wales
Theater than revisions were being discussed. On June 16, in they
went.
   ``You rehearse it in front of Frank Rich, basically,'' said
actress Kathleen Rowe McAllen, referring to The New York Times
critic who saw the show at the June 17 matinee.
   ``It's a matter of fine tuning and honing,'' co-lyricist Don
Black said. ``There were certain things we wanted to do (before the
opening), and there wasn't really time.''
   The changes in ``Aspects'' focus on McAllen's character,
Giulietta, an Italian sculptress who has affairs with both an aging
English aristocrat (Kevin Colson), and his younger wife, a French
actress (Ann Crumb).
   A new song in the second act, ``There's More to Love Than Making
Love,'' replaces the initial ``With Other Men'' to make Giulietta
more than just a ``promiscuous Italian,'' said McAllen.
   Originally, the show ended where it began _ at a train station
in Pau in southwest France, as the romantic lead (Michael Ball)
prepared to leave with Giulietta possibly in tow.
   Now, it ends in the aristocrat's garden with the romantic leads
in a clear romantic clinch. Of all the musical's permutations, here
at last is one that may endure, and the new ending is meant to
satisfy audiences who may have felt confused or let down by the
original finale.
   ``It finishes on a high,'' said Black, who went on to quote his
American colleague, composer-lyricist Stephen Sondheim: ``Stephen
says, `Musicals aren't written, they're rewritten,' and this is
very much the case.
   ``It's not like the old days on the road where you sling a song
out or write a new scene. You have to live with a score and let it
settle to see if it sits properly with the audience.''
   In London, too, preview periods are much briefer than on
Broadway, so that adjustments are more easily made after the
opening.
   Black said ``Aspects'' was now frozen for London but would no
doubt change further when it opens on Broadway next April. ``The
tinkering isn't done.''
   Echoed critic Mark Steyn in The Independent newspaper, ``While
the show has been sharpened ... `Aspects' still has much to be
fixed.''
   ``Follies,'' ``Les Miserables'' and ``Chess'' are other recent
shows that changed during their London engagements.
   But the phenomenon is not limited to blockbuster musicals of the
1980s.
   Oscar Wilde's 1895 masterpiece ``The Importance of Being
Earnest'' was originally in four acts. The version now being
performed has three.
   Tennessee Williams wrote two separate third acts for his 1955
``Cat on a Hot Tin Roof.'' More recently, producer Joseph Papp shut
down rehearsals of Albert Innaurato's ``Coming of Age in Soho''
off-Broadway to allow the playwright to overhaul his play.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Thurs Aug. 10</NOTE>
</DOC>
