<HEAD>$adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, Aug. 14</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Monday, August 14, the 226th day of 1989. There are 139
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   Twenty years ago, on August 14, 1969, British troops arrived in
Northern Ireland to intervene in the sectarian violence between
Protestants and Roman Catholics. The conflict since has claimed the
lives of more than 2,700 people.
   On this date:
   In 1848, the Oregon Territory was established.
   In 1900, international forces _ including U.S. Marines _ entered
Beijing to put down the Boxer Rebellion, which was aimed at ridding
China of foreigners.
   In 1917, China declared war on Germany and Austria at the start
of World War I.
   In 1935, the Social Security Act became law, creating
unemployment insurance and pension plans for the elderly.
   In 1941, President Franklin Roosevelt and British Prime Minister
Winston Churchill signed the Atlantic Charter.
   In 1945, President Truman announced that Japan had
unconditionally surrendered, ending the hostilities of World War II.
   In 1947, Pakistan became independent of British rule.
   In 1951, newspaper publisher William Randolph Hearst died in
Beverly Hills, Calif.
   In 1962, robbers held up a U.S. mail truck in Plymouth, Mass.,
making off with more than $1.5 million.
   In 1973, the U.S. bombing of Cambodia came to a halt, marking
the official end to 12 years of American combat in Indochina.
   In 1980, President Carter and Vice President Walter Mondale were
nominated for a second term in office at the Democratic National
Convention in New York.
   Ten years ago: The State Department acknowledged that UN
Ambassador Andrew Young had held an unauthorized meeting with a
representative of the Palestine Liberation Organization, in
apparent violation of U.S. policy.
   Five years ago: The Soviet Union denounced President Reagan's
off-the-record joke, made three days earlier, in which he said he
was set to begin bombing Russia.
   One year ago: President Reagan arrived in New Orleans on the eve
of the Republican National Convention that would nominate Vice
President George Bush to succeed him.
   Today's Birthdays: Newspaper columnist Russell Baker is 64.
Singer Buddy Greco is 63. Actress Alice Ghostley is 63. Rock singer
David Crosby is 48. Actress Susan Saint James is 43.
   Thought for Today: ``No one can build his security upon the
nobleness of another person.'' _ Willa Cather, American author
(1873-1947).
</TEXT>
