<HEAD>For Release Wednesday, Aug. 16</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Wednesday, August 16, the 228th day of 1989. There are
137 days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On August 16, 1977, the ``King of Rock `n` Roll,'' Elvis
Presley, died of a heart ailment at Graceland Mansion in Memphis,
Tenn., at age 42.
   On this date:
   In 1777, American forces won an important victory of the
Revolutionary War at the Battle of Bennington, Vt.
   In 1812, Detroit fell to British and Indian forces in the War of
1812.
   In 1829, the original ``Siamese twins,'' Chang and Eng Bunker,
arrived in Boston to be exhibited to the Western world.
   In 1858, a telegraphed message from Britain's Queen Victoria to
U.S. President James Buchanan was transmitted over the recently
laid transatlantic cable.
   In 1861, President Abraham Lincoln prohibited the states of the
Union from trading with the seceding states of the Confederacy.
   In 1894, labor leader George Meany was born, in New York City.
   In 1896, gold was found at Bonanza Creek, Alaska.
   In 1948, baseball legend Babe Ruth died in New York at age 53.
   In 1956, Adlai E. Stevenson was nominated for president at the
Democratic convention in Chicago.
   In 1960, Britain granted independence to the crown colony of
Cyprus.
   In 1978, James Earl Ray, convicted assassin of Dr. Martin Luther
King Jr., told a Capitol Hill hearing he did not commit the crime,
saying he'd been set up by a mysterious man called ``Raoul.''
   In 1987, 156 people were killed when Northwest Airlines Flight
255 crashed while trying to take off from a Detroit airport; the
sole survivor was 4-year-old Cecelia Cichan.
   In 1987, thousands of people worldwide began a two-day
celebration of the ``harmonic convergence,'' which heralded what
believers called the start of a new, purer age of humankind.
   Ten years ago: The Federal Reserve Board increased its discount
rate, charged to banks which borrow from the Fed, to 10.5 percent,
in an effort to control inflation at the cost of worsening the
nation's recession.
   Five years ago: A federal jury in Los Angeles acquitted former
automaker John Z. De Lorean of all eight counts in a cocaine
conspiracy indictment.
   One year ago: Vice President George Bush tapped Indiana Senator
Dan Quayle to be his running mate, calling him ``a man of the
future.''
   Today's Birthdays: Former Israeli Prime Minister Menachem Begin
is 76. Israeli Deputy Prime Minister and Finance Minister Shimon
Peres is 66. Actor Fess Parker is 64. Actress Ann Blyth is 61.
Actor Robert Culp is 59. Sportscaster Frank Gifford is 59. Singer
Eydie Gorme is 57. Actress Julie Newmar is 54. Actress Anita
Gillette is 53. Actress Carole Shelley is 50. Actress Lesley Ann
Warren is 43. Singer Madonna is 31. Actor Timothy Hutton is 29.
   Thought for Today: ``To feel that one has a place in life solves
half the problem of contentment.'' _ George Edward Woodberry,
American poet, critic and educator (1855-1930).
</TEXT>
