<SECOND>BC-History, Adv17,0629</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thursday, Aug. 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Thursday, Aug. 17, the 229th day of 1989. There are 136
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   Twenty years ago, Hurricane Camille slammed into the Gulf Coast
with winds clocked at more than 170 mph and gusts over 200 mph.
More than 250 people died, most of them in the Mississippi Delta,
after warnings about the approaching storm apparently went largely
unheeded.
   On this date:
   In 1863, Federal ships bombarded Fort Sumter in Charleston
harbor during the Civil War.
   In 1807, Robert Fulton's North River Steam Boat began chugging
up New York's Hudson River on its successful round-trip journey to
Albany.
   In 1915, a mob lynched Jewish businessman Leo Frank in Cobb
County, Georgia, after Frank's death sentence for the murder of a
13-year-old girl had been commuted to life imprisonment.
   In 1939, the MGM movie musical ``The Wizard of Oz'' opened at
the Loew's Capitol Theater in New York, two days after premiering
at Grauman's Chinese Theater in Hollywood.
   In 1940, President Franklin D. Roosevelt and Canadian Prime
Minister William Mackenzie King met in Ogdensburg, New York, where
they agreed to set up a joint defense commission.
   In 1942, U.S. bombers staged their first independent raid on
Europe, attacking Rouen, France.
   In 1943, Allied forces gained control of Sicily.
   In 1948, former State Department official Alger Hiss faced his
chief accuser, Whittaker Chambers, during a closed-door meeting in
New York of the House Un-American Activities Committee, and
repeated his denial that he'd ever been a Communist agent.
   In 1962, East German border guards shot and mortally wounded
18-year-old Peter Fechter, who had attempted to cross the Berlin
Wall into the western sector.
   In 1969, the Woodstock Music and Art Fair concluded near Bethel,
N.Y.
   In 1978, the first successful trans-Atlantic balloon flight
ended as Maxie Anderson, Ben Abruzzo and Larry Newman landed their
``Double Eagle Two'' in a wheat field outside Paris.
   In 1982, a federal jury in South Bend, Ind., acquitted
self-avowed racist Joseph Paul Franklin of charges he had violated
the civil rights of former National Urban League director Vernon
Jordan by shooting and wounding Jordan outside a Fort Wayne motel
in 1980.
   In 1983, lyricist Ira Gershwin, who wrote such classic songs as
```S Wonderful'' and ``The Man I Love'' with his composer brother
George, died in Beverly Hills, Calif., at age 86.
   In 1987, Rudolf Hess, the last member of Adolf Hitler's inner
circle, died at a Berlin hospital near Spandau Prison at age 93,
having apparently committed suicide by strangling himself with an
electrical cord.
   In 1987, the Dow Jones Industrial Average closed above 2,700 for
the first time.
   Ten years ago: President Jimmy Carter boarded the Delta Queen,
an old-fashioned stern-wheeler, in St. Paul, Minn., to begin a
weeklong trip down the Mississippi River to garner support for his
energy policies.
   Five years ago: As delegates to the Republican National
Convention began to arrive in Dallas, the platform committee put
the finishing touches on its statement of party doctrine, which
said the GOP was seeing ``a new dawn of the American spirit.''
   One year ago: Vice President George Bush was nominated for
president at the Republican National Convention in New Orleans.
Pakistani President Mohammad Zia ul-Haq and U.S. Ambassador Arnold
Raphel were killed in a plane crash.
   Today's birthdays: Actress Maureen O'Hara is 69. Actor Robert
DeNiro is 46. Singer Belinda Carlisle is 31. Actor Sean Penn is 29.
   Thought for today: ``Some are weatherwise, some are otherwise.''
_ Benjamin Franklin, American statesman, inventor and writer
(1706-1790).
</TEXT>
