<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     08-07 0907</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0949</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fewer thrift institutions, lower deposit rates
for savers and reduced property values in some regions will result
from the landmark savings and loan legislation passed by Congress,
analysts say.
   The 1,000-page bill, adopted early Saturday, is the most
significant financial law adopted since the Depression. As the
largest government bailout ever, it will cost each taxpayer about
$1,000 over 30 years to close or merge hundreds of insolvent thrift
institutions hemorrhaging losses at the rate of $20 million a day.
   The measure provides the most sweeping reorganization of the
regulatory bureaucracy in 50 years. Beyond that, in highly visible
and more subtle ways, it touches anyone who pays taxes, deposits
money with a bank or S&amp;L, or owns real estate.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Civilian unemployment dipped by 0.1 percentage
point to 5.2 percent in July, the government said. Analysts say the
data should ease fears of an imminent recession but heighten
concerns about inflation.
   Joblessness was down from 5.3 percent in June, with non-farm
businesses adding 169,000 jobs, the Labor Department said Friday.
   ``This suggests an economy that is clearly, clearly far from a
recession,'' said Elliot Platt, senior vice president of the
securities firm Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Computer Inc. reluctantly recommended that
its shareholders accept a buyout by J.H. Whitney &amp; Co. for about
$1.1 billion, $74 million less than Whitney's previous offer.
   Prime's board of directors said Friday the merger was still
preferable to selling its minicomputer business to MAI Basic Four
Inc. of Tustin, Calif., which has offered $525 million for the
division.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trans World Airlines Inc. has suspended
contract talks with its largest union because of the possibility of
a merger or change in management at the airline, a union spokesman
said.
   The company, owned by takeover specialist Carl Icahn, confirmed
Friday that the talks had been halted, but refused to say why.
   Icahn had previously expressed interest in buying strikebound
Eastern Airlines and had been in extensive talks with that
carrier's unions.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Los Angeles investor Alfred Checchi has
signed the acquisition papers to complete his group's $3.65 billion
buyout of NWA Inc., the parent of Northwest Airlines.
   The 41-year-old former Marriott Corp. treasurer said Friday that
all publicly held shares of NWA common stock have been purchased
for $121 each, officially ending the takeover battle initiated by
Checchi in late March.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate approved legislation to boost
companies' liability for oil spills, create a nationwide system to
clean them up and establish a $1 billion trust fund to help
compensate for damages.
   The oil-spill legislation was approved Friday, a little more
than four months after the tanker Exxon Valdez struck a reef in
Alaska's Prince William Sound, rupturing the ship's hull and
spilling 11 million gallons of oil that stained the coastline with
sticky black ooze.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A defense lawyer said there no telling how many
people will be indicted as a result of the ongoing federal probe
into fraudulent trading at the world's largest futures exchanges,
but it could be as many as 200.
   Attorney George Collins, asked about a published report saying
the next few months could bring an additional 100 indictments, said
Friday the government could seek many more than that _ or less.
   U.S. Attorney Anton Valukas' office has declined comment about
the breadth of the investigation into trading at the Chicago Board
of Trade and the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency banned
household ant killers containing the chemical sodium arsenate
because of the danger of small children ingesting the compounds.
   The EPA said Friday the chemical is used to kill ants that are
merely a nuisance and do not threaten human health, food crops or
wood structures.
   EPA spokesman Ed Heier said the product is a surgary liquid made
by several companies and sold under numerous brand names. He said
that because the purchaser normally applies the ant killer and
leaves it exposed, it is not child-proof.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Test wells have confirmed the discovery
of a major oil reservoir near the Prudhoe Bay field on Alaska's
North Slope, Arco Alaska Inc. said.
   Arco Alaska, a division of Atlantic Richfield Co., said Friday
that a test well 2{ miles west of the 1988 discovery well at Point
McIntyre produced flow rates up to 5,400 barrels a day. Arco
spokeswoman Susan Andrews said that would make it one of the
largest oil discoveries in the United States in 10 years.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walt Disney Co.'s stock price reversed
direction after rising this past week as speculation that it was a
takeover target died down.
   Disney shares dropped $4.87{ a share to close at $116.12{ Friday
in active trading on the New York Stock Exchange. It had risen
$11.25 a share in the previous two days.
</TEXT>
