<DOCNO> AP890807-0147 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-89 0819EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Register-MailSale     08-07 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Register-Mail Sale,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Owners of Galesburg Newspaper File Lawsuit Seeking to Void Sale Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GALESBURG, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The deadline for sale of the Galesburg
Register-Mail to Thomson Newspaper of Toronto has passed, so the
Illinois newspaper's owners hope to void the sale agreement.
   The Register-Mail's owners have filed a lawsuit in U.S. District
Court asking that the $14.7 million contract with Thomson be
declared null and void.
   The Peoria Journal Star has made two tender offers for the
Register-Mail and two weekly newspapers, the Wrova Reporter and the
Galva News. Those offers are to expire on Thursday.
   One offer, for $15 million, involves creation of an employee
stock ownership plan, which offers significant tax benefits. The
second offer is for $16 million for a direct purchase.
   The lawsuit filed Friday states that Thomson repeatedly said it
would call off the deal if its purchase of the Register-Mail was
not completed as scheduled on June 30.
   ``Thomson now claims that its contract with the signing
shareholders is valid and enforceable and that it will neither
permit a sale to the Peoria Journal Star nor an unrestricted public
auction,'' the complaint stated.
   About 91 percent of the Register-Mail's shares already had been
tendered to Thomson when Judge Michael Mihm issued an injunction
blocking the sale on June 30.
   Former Register-Mail publisher John Pritchard, who also is a
trustee of a trust that controls 54 percent of the newspaper's
stock, asked for the injunction on the grounds that the other two
trustees had breached their fiduciary responsibilities by not
adequately considering other offers. He also charged that the two _
his brother, Lester Pritchard, and their cousin, Sally Day _ agreed
to sell to Thomson because of payments that would have bypassed the
trust.
   All three trustees joined together in Friday's action to void
the Thomson deal.
   Thomson has appealed Mihm's injunction to the 7th Circuit Court
of Appeals in Chicago, but a hearing has not yet been scheduled.
   Along with the injunction, Mihm had voided the tendering of the
trust's shares to Thomson and ordered the appointment of an
investment banker to evaluate all offers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
