<FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-89 1055EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Eastern-Pilots 1stLd-Writethru   08-07 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Pilots, 1st Ld-Writethru,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Pilots Favor Continuing Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS with new grafs 1-13 to UPDATE with details of pilots'
meetings, votes; picks up 6th graf pvs bg'ng, _Continuing the ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking Eastern Airlines pilots generally remain
opposed to returning to work following meetings in several of the
carrier's major cities, a pilots union spokesman said today.
   Air Line Pilots Association members in Atlanta, New York and
Miami met on Sunday to discuss whether to continue the
five-month-old walkout, said ALPA spokesman Ron Cole.
   ``All the feedback we've gotten says there is strong support for
remaining on strike,'' said Cole.
   ALPA officials say formal votes are scheduled for today in
Atlanta and Tuesday in Miami.
   ALPA members in Boston, Washington and Tampa, Fla., could listen
to the Miami meeting via an audio link, but Cole was not certain
whether pilots in those cities cast votes.
   During a closed-door meeting in Miami on Sunday, some pilots
booed and stormed out after a return-to-work option was presented
by Jack Bavis, the head of Eastern's pilots union, according to
published reports. One pilot pushed a television cameraman who was
outside the meeting room.
   Cole said only a few pilots at the meeting said they have
contemplated returning to work.
   Some pilots circulated petitions suggesting that ALPA's national
leadership was not giving full support to striking Eastern pilots
and advocated a nationwide pilot work stoppage on Labor Day.
   Karen Ceremsak, a spokeswoman for the Miami-based carrier, said
a few pilots called Sunday to indicate they wanted to return to
work.
   The 20-member pilots' Master Executive Council voted in favor of
continuing the strike on Saturday following a five-day meeting in
Washington.
   ``Your MEC voted unanimously to continue the picket line,'' the
union's taped telephone message said, adding that the union
leadership repeated its commitment to long-term pilots' security.
   ``Remember how important it is to hold the line while all these
dynamic forces affecting our situation and the alternatives are
played out,'' the message said.
   Among the options to be proposed at the Tuesday ALPA meeting in
Miami are:
   _Continuing the strike and support of the buyout effort by
Chicago options trader Joseph Ritchie.
   _Negotiating a settlement with Eastern management. The Air Line
Pilots Association's chief goals in negotiations have been job
security for its 3,600 Eastern members, ensuring Eastern's survival
and unionizing pilots at Continental Airlines, Eastern's sister
carrier under Texas Air Corp. ownership.
   _Returning to work unilaterally. The pilots are on sympathy
strike, and their contract remains in effect.
   The last scenario would raise legal questions about how many
pilots Eastern would have to take back at their existing salaries,
considerably higher than those of newly hired pilots.
   Eastern, which admitted its Machinists strike contingency plans
were crippled by the pilots' surprising solidarity, has been moving
along on a rebuilding plan without its unions.
   The airline filed March 9 for Chapter 11 bankruptcy
reorganization, five days after the Machinists went on strike and
were joined by the pilots and flight attendants. Eastern has filed
a plan for its creditors that envisions an airline two-thirds' its
pre-strike size, coming out of bankruptcy by year's end.
   Eastern says it will need 1,700 pilots. By week's end, Eastern
said 380 ALPA pilots had crossed the picket line, more than 300
newly hired pilots have completed training and 700 more are in
training.
   Eastern has indicated that most of the striking pilots no longer
have jobs to come back to. The pilots union would likely challenge
that.
   From the outset, Eastern management has said it doesn't need the
striking Machinists, whose 8,500 members include mechanics, baggage
handlers and other ground services workers. But the unions, with
some backing in Congress, have chaged that consumer safety could be
compromised by Eastern's heavy reliance on newly hired pilots.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
