<FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-89 1116EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-UALOffer     08-07 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UAL Offer,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Airline Gets Takeover Bid From Investor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investor Marvin Davis has made an unsolicited and
conditional offer to acquire UAL Corp., parent of United Airlines,
company officials announced today.
   The bid, reportedly worth $200 a share or $4.32 billion, sent
UAL stock soaring in heavy trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
By late morning, UAL was up $36.50 to $201 a share.
   The board of UAL is to consider the proposal at a Wednesday
meeting, the officials said.
   ``While the board of directors has not decided whether a sale of
the company is in the best interest of the company's shareholders
and other constituencies, in keeping with its fiduciary duty, the
board will give careful consideration to Mr. Davis' proposal,''
Stephen M. Wolf, UAL chairman and president, said in a news release.
   UAL spokesman Rob Doughty refused to comment beyond Wolf's
statement and would not say what Davis offered for Chicago-based
UAL.
   However, the Wall Street Journal reported in today's editions
that Davis, a former oil wildcatter, has offered $200 a share, or a
total of about $4.32 billion for the airline.
   UAL stock has risen sharply since Los Angeles investor Alfred
Checchi made a successful $3.65 billion bid in June for NWA Inc.,
the parent of Northwest Airlines.
   UAL stock rose from $117.50 in mid-June to $190 in late July.
The movement was fueled by speculation that investors such as
Robert Bass and Davis had purchased stakes in UAL.
   However, the price of the stock has settled in recent trading,
closing at $164.50 on Friday amid reports that the U.S.
Transportation Department would no longer look kindly on leveraged
takeovers of major U.S. airlines.
   The offer from Davis comes at a time when the airline is
experiencing some troubles. In July, United had its second fatal
accident in six months when a DC-10 crash-landed in Sioux City,
Iowa, killing 111 of the 296 passengers and crew aboard.
   In February, the cargo door of a Boeing 747 blew out over the
Pacific Ocean on a flight from Honolulu to Auckland, New Zealand,
killing nine.
   United, recently surpassed by American as the nation's largest
airline, lrofit from a year earlier.
   For the quarter ended June 30, the airline reported net income
of $141 million, or $6.52 per share on revenue of $2.5 billion. The
company had revenue of $8.98 billion in 1988.
</TEXT>
