<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Prices Climb on Follow-Through Buying After Last Week's
Lows</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mostly higher
today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Analysts said the climb was expected, and resulted from
follow-through buying that began on Friday. Beans slid to a series
of contract lows last week because of wet weather, and weren't
helped by the low volume in mid-week as many traders stayed on the
sidelines because of sweeping fraud indictments announced by the
U.S. attorney's office.
   Volume could stay on the low side this week also as traders
await two important crop estimates, the first due tomorrow from
influential private forecaster Conrad Leslie, the second expected
Thursday from the U.S. Department of Agriculture.
   At the open, wheat was { cent lower to \ cent higher, with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.87} a bushel; corn was 2
cents to 3{ cents higher, with September at $2.23 a bushel; oats
were 1{ cents to 2 cents higher, with September at $1.42 a bushel;
and soybeans were unchanged to 5\ cents higher, August at $5.96 a
bushel.
   Livestock and pork futures prices were mixed on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .22 cent lower to .28 cent higher, with August
at 73.95 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent lower to .20
cent higher, with August at 84.70 cents a pound; live hogs were .20
cent lower to .08 cent higher, with August at 46.60 cents a pound;
.12 cent lower to 1 cent higher, with August at 26.15 cents a pound.
