<FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-89 1612EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Merc-Eagleton     08-07 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Merc-Eagleton,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Senator Eagleton Criticizes Merc Reform Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former U.S. Sen. Thomas Eagleton on Monday
criticized reforms recently announced by the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange and asked the Commodity Futures Trading Commission to
impose more stringent measures on the Merc.
   Eagleton, a public member of the exchange's board of governors
and a member of a special committee whose work led to the reforms,
said the changes announced Aug. 3 are a positive step but do not go
nearly far enough.
   The reforms, announced just one day after 46 traders were
indicted, call for tougher rules and penalties and increased
surveillance of the trading floor. One official said they are
designed ``to put the fear of God into the membership.''
   He said the public outcry system of ``grunts, groans and
gestures'' permits only limited accountability and limited ability
to trace transactions.
   Eagleton also called for more clout for floor inspectors and an
even tighter audit trail.
   ``The Commodity Futures Trading Commission has to awake from its
long slumber and realize that the people's multi-billion-dollar
business in Chicago has to be vigorously supervised by the people's
regulatory agency,'' the Missouri Democrat said.
   Leo Melamed, chairman of the Merc's executive committee, said
the reforms were first discussed in January by Merc officials who
appointed a blue-ribbon panel, including Eagleton, to review
procedures on the floor in response to public disclosure of a
2{-year undercover federal investigation at the Merc and the
Chicago Board of Trade.
   The Board of Trade announced similar measures late Wednesday,
within hours of the indictment.
   The most significant rule change approved by the Merc's Board of
Governors, however, requires membership approval.
   It would severely limit dual trading, in which a trader is
allowed to trade his own account as well as customers' accounts _ a
practice that appears to have made possible many of the frauds
alleged in the indictment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
