<FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-89 1649EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     08-07 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0459</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Gains, Gold Slips</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged higher against most key
currencies in thin trading Monday, extending last week's rally,
which stemmed from speculation that interest rates aren't likely to
decline soon.
   Gold prices slipped. On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold
bullion for current delivery fell to $365.90 a troy ounce from
$367.25 Friday. Republic National Bank of New York said the late
bid for gold was $365.20 an ounce, off $2.30.
   Currency traders said the dollar continued to be buoyed by
Friday's better-than-expected employment figures, which showed
nonfarm payrolls rose by 169,000 in July. The jobless rate for last
month also fell to 5.2 percent from 5.3 percent in June.
   The news dampened expectations that the Federal Reserve would
further lower interest rates since it shows that the economy is
still growing, traders said.
   ``The Friday number was a watershed event in terms of short- and
intermediate-term thinking toward the dollar,'' said J. Thomas
Stanley, a vice president at Chemical New York Capital Markets
Group.
   Higher interest rates are seen as bullish for the dollar because
they make dollar-denominated securities, such as stocks and bonds,
more attractive to foreigners, thereby increasing the need to
convert their currencies into dollars.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar closed at 139.78 Japanese yen, up from 138.05.
The dollar closed lower in London at 139.47 yen, and higher in New
York at 140.05 yen, up from 139.85.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6075, cheaper for buyers
than Friday's $1.6150. Sterling fetched $1.5980 in New York, down
from $1.6060.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.9160 West German marks, up from 1.9070; 1.6475
Swiss francs, up from 1.6435; 1.17355 Canadian dollars, down from
1.17825; 6.4830 French francs, up from 6.4555; and 1,377.50 Italian
lire, up from 1,370.50.
   Late dollar rates in Europe compared with Friday: 1.9055 West
German marks, up from 1.8975; 1.6380 Swiss francs, up from 1.6353;
6.4470 French francs, up from 6.4260; 2.1502 Dutch guilders, up
from 2.1300; 1.1745 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1775; and
1,373.50 Italian lire, up from 1,366.00.
   The late bid for gold was $365.75 an ounce in London, down from
$370.75 Friday. Gold fell in Zurich to $365.40 an ounce from
$370.50.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed at $367.65 an ounce, down
from $371.95.
   Silver prices also lost ground. On New York's Comex, silver
bullion for current delivery slipped to $5.128 a troy ounce from
$5.168 Friday. Silver settled at $5.18 an ounce in London, down
from $5.23.
</TEXT>
