<FIRST>r f AM-Yeutter-FeedGrains     08-07 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yeutter-Feed Grains,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agriculture Secretary Says Farmers Can Compete If Trade Barriers
Reduced</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress faces a ``long, hard, bruising battle''
over the 1990 farm bill but could have the job done by next summer,
U.S. Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter said Monday.
   Yeutter also said the United States will continue to push for
elimination of the barriers to fair agricultural trade around the
world.
   In a speech to the U.S. Feed Grains Council, Yeutter said he
expects ``heavy debate'' on new federal farm legislation in
February and March, as Congress tries to approve a farm bill before
the 1990 elections.
   Yeutter said he disagrees with those who want the United States
to limit farm production and sell less grain overseas. He said
there will be 6.2 billion people in the world by the year 2000.
   ``Somebody is going to feed those folks,'' said Yeutter. ``I
hope that somebody will include U.S. feed grain producers.'
   He also said he opposes international agreements in which
exporting countries try to divide up markets and regulate prices.
   ``I'd rather compete than negotiate market shares,'' he said.
   Yeutter said U.S. officials attending the next round of
international trade negotiations will work for reform of policies
that limit imports, subsidize exports and create high internal
price supports for farmers.
   Such practices distort free trade, he said.
   The European Community, for example, has reduced its imports of
coarse grains from 20 million metric tons a year to 4 million tons
a year in 10 years, while its exports of grain have increased from
5 million to 12 million tons, said Yeutter.
   ``That's an enormous turn-around thanks to these export
subsidies,'' he said. ``Let's phase out all the distortions ... and
let farmers compete.''
   One approach, said Yeutter, would be to persuade nations to
replace all import constraints _ quotas, for example _ with
tariffs, then work to gradually reduce them.
   Until trade reform is accomplished, however, Yeutter said the
United States will need to provide export subsidies to compete with
other producers like the European Community.
   Yeutter also said U.S. farmers will have to be more competitive
so that they can take advantage of foreign sales opportunities when
trade barriers are removed.
   ``We better be ready to get them when the markets exist,'' said
Yeutter.
   During the meeting, Yeutter also announced that the United
States and the Soviet Union will begin negotiations in December for
a new, long-term grain agreement.
   The current agreement provides that the Soviets will buy at
least 4 million metric tons each of U.S. wheat and corn annually,
and make additional purchases of at least 1 million tons of wheat,
corn, soybeans or soybean meal.
   It also allows the Soviets to buy up to 3 million metric tons of
additional wheat and corn without additional consultations.
   The U.S. Feed Grains Council, a private organization of farm and
agribusiness groups, was formed in 1960 to promote export markets
for U.S. corn, barley and sorghum.
   About 300 people are expected to attend the annual meeting,
which concludes Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
