<FIRST>r f AM-US-MexicoDebt     08-07 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Mexico Debt,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Critics Question Value of Cutting Mexican Debt</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Baker-Mexico, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A conservative critic of Treasury Secretary
Nicholas F. Brady's plan for cutting Third World debt said on
Monday that Mexico needs to privatize more of its industry and cut
the number of bureaucrats so that Mexicans will be encouraged to
bring home the billions they have sent to the United States and
other safe havens.
   He said that Mexico has more government employees than the
United States, which has three times Mexico's population.
   ``We haven't heard anything about debt-equity swaps _ cancelling
foreign debt in return for shares in Mexican industry,'' said
Edward L. Hudgins, director of the Center for International
Economic Growth. The center is part of the Heritage Foundation, a
conservative private study group.
   ``It's not inflationary as Mexican officials say. Some of those
shares are owned by the government. They can be turned over in
return for debt.''
   Earlier Monday Brady said that last month's agreement between
the Mexican government and creditor banks to reduce $54 billion
worth of Mexico's foreign debt has brought the country so much
investment from abroad that a $2 billion ``bridge loan'' he had
promised may be less necessary. Brady spoke at a news conference in
Mexico City.
   The Mexican agreement has aroused criticism as well as praise in
recent days.
   Sir Kit McMahon, chairman of Britain's Midland Bank, called it
ill-conceived and destabilizing, encouraging debtor countries to
slow down repayments. Netherlands Finance Minister H. Onno Ruding,
head of the International Monetary Fund's powerful Interim
Committee, said he would not ask his taxpayers to finance payments
to American banks.
   William R. Cline, a senior fellow at the Institute for
International Economics, reported that an estimated $2.5 billion
had been brought back to Mexico since the agreement. Some estimates
put the total of ``capital flight'' from Mexico as high as $80
billion. Mexico's foreign debt is calculated by the World Bank at
more than $107 billion.
   Cline agreed with Brady that the agreement had improved public
confidence so much in Mexico that domestic interest rates had come
down enough to save the Mexican government $10 billion a year.
Cline estimated that it will save Mexico another $1 billion to $1.5
billion a year of the interest it has been paying on foreign debt.
   The institute is a private research body with international
funding.
   Though he saw the plan as a good start, Cline said that about
$34 billion pledged to support it by the fund, the World Bank and
Japan would not be enough _ that at least $50 billion will be
needed.
   Third World debt is estimated at $1.3 trillion.
</TEXT>
