<HEAD>Ames Sells G.C. Murphy, Bargain World</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCKY HILL, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ames Department Stores Inc. on Monday
sold its G.C. Murphy Co. and Bargain World variety stores to E-II
Holdings Inc. of York, Pa., parent company of McCrory Corp., for
$80 million.
   G.C. Murphy, of McKeesport, Pa., near Pittsburgh, operates 130
variety stores and 25 Bargain World stores in 13 states.
   The stores had a combined revenue of $175 million in the year
ended Jan. 28 and employ about 3,500 people, mostly in
Pennsylvania, Ohio, West Virginia, Maryland and Virginia, according
to Ames spokesman Bill Roberts.
   Ames purchased G.C. Murphy, then with 383 stores, in 1985 for
about $196.5 million.
   Since the purchase, Ames has closed 128 G.C. Murphy and Murphy
Mart stores in 19 states and converted many Murphy Mart stores to
Ames outlets.
   E-II Holdings is a subsidiary of Riklis Family Corp. and
operates about 1,300 variety stores through McCrory Corp.,
officials said.
   Ames said its purchase of the Zayre chain of 388 department
stores last year doubled its size and made its Murphy stores a
small part of its operation.
   Ames said it will use the proceeds of the sale to reduce the
long-term bank debt incurred in the purchase of Zayre.
   The McCrory chain, with about 1,300 outlets the nation's largest
variety store chain, also includes Newberry, TG&amp;Y, H.L. Green,
McLellan and Kress stores.
   Fisher said the newly acquired stores will retain their current
names. He said no layoffs are planned.
   G.C. Murphy's headquarters and distribution center in McKeesport
will remain with Ames, according to Ewing.
</TEXT>
