<SECOND>AM-AT&amp;T-MCI, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0276,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>AT&amp;T Accuses MCI of Illegal Discounting</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS new penultimate graf: ``Herb Linnen,'' with AT&amp;T figure
on market share. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. on Monday
accused its biggest competitor, MCI Corp., of offering large
business customers illegally low prices to win their long-distance
telephone business.
   AT&amp;T officials said they hope the complaint will lead to a
reversal of a Federal Communications Commission policy that exempts
AT&amp;T competitors from having to file tariffs with the FCC detailing
rates and other terms they offer customers.
   In its complaint to the FCC, AT&amp;T alleged that MCI has used
unlawful discriminatory discounts the past two years to win
contracts with the Pentagon, Merrill Lynch; Westin, Hilton and
Vista hotels; United Airlines, the University of Colorado and
Uniguard Security Insurance Co.
   ``The commission's regulatory reforms have not kept pace with
the fierce growth of interexchange competition,'' Francine J.
Perry, AT&amp;T's vice president for legal affairs, said in a letter to
the FCC accompanying the complaint.
   To promote competition in long-distance and data transmission
services with the then-impending breakup of the Bell System, the
FCC in 1983 granted ``forbearance'' to non-dominant carriers on
filing rate tariffs with the commission.
   AT&amp;T said it viewed that decision as a ``transitional, interim
step'' that would lead to ``eliminating ... unnecessary regulatory
restraints'' _ such as disclosing its rate offerings to business
customers _ for all long-distance carriers, including itself.
   Because AT&amp;T alone has to file tariffs with the FCC, ``MCI and
other competitors have gained unwarranted advantages in the
marketplace by selectively providing services on an off-tariff
basis,'' Berry said.
   MCI, which filed a similar complaint against AT&amp;T last year
after AT&amp;T won a contract for Holiday Inns' long-distance and
reservation system, called Monday's complaint a ``smokescreen.''
   ``AT&amp;T is merely trying to achieve its own deregulation through
the complaint process,'' said Pam Small, an MCI spokeswoman.
``They're essentially challenging the rules.''
   Ms. Small said MCI maintains that AT&amp;T should still be required
to detail its rates through tariff filings with the FCC because, as
the dominant carrier, it still holds 80 percent of the
long-distance and interstate data transmission market.
   Herb Linnen, spokesman for AT&amp;T, said FCC figures show the
company holds about 68 percent of the market, far less than the
almost-total control it once held.
   Generally, in telecomunications or other regulated industries,
companies must adhere to tariffs filed with regulators.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890807-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-89 2042EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Dunkin'Donuts     08-07 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dunkin' Donuts,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Denies Injunction Against Dunkin' Donuts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Delaware judge refused Monday to stop Dunkin'
Donuts Inc. from taking anti-takeover measures that put about 28
percent of the company's stock in friendly hands.
   Vice Chancellor William Chandler of Delaware Chancery Court
denied a request by a Canadian partnership for a preliminary
injunction against the doughnut company's $35 million employee
stock ownership plan and its $28 million sale of preferred stock to
General Electric Capital Corp.
   The Canadian partners, Unicorp Canada Corp.'s Kingsbridge
Capital Group and Cara Operations Limited, launched a $305 million
hostile tender for Dunkin' Donuts in June.
   The doughnut chain, based in Randolph, has franchised more than
1,700 doughnut shops worldwide. It reported a profit of $13.5
million on sales of $112.8 million last year.
   Kingsbridge and Cara argued in the lawsuit that Dunkin' Donuts
enacted the ESOP and sold the preferred stock to GE Capital to
frustrate a takeover under Delaware's business combination statute,
which effectively requires a hostile bidder to obtain 85 percent of
the target firm's outstanding common stock.
   The ESOP holds about 16 percent of Dunkin Donuts' outstanding
common shares, and GE Capital's preferred stock is convertible to
700,000 common shares, or roughly an 11 percent stake in the
company.
   Since top executives and directors also hold about 15 percent of
the shares, more than 40 percent of Dunkin' Donuts is considered by
securities analysts to be in friendly hands.
   Dunkin' Donuts attorney John D. Donovan Jr. said the judge
accepted the doughnut maker's contention that the ESOP and GE
Capital had caused ``no immediate and irreparable harm'' to the
Canadians.
   ``We argued that if the ESOP and GE Capital don't want to tender
their shares, it's because the bid is at a bargain basement price,
not because they don't have a right to do so,'' Donovan said.
   Gil Sparks, attorney for the Canadian partnership, was on
vacation Monday and could not be reached, according to a
receptionist at his office in Wilmington, Del. There was no answer
after business hours at Kingsbridge's Toronto headquarters, and
Kingsbridge spokesman Eric W. Evans did not return messages left at
his home.
</TEXT>
