<FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-89 2108EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-FirstInterstate     08-07 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-First Interstate,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Interstate to Sell Finance-Lease Subsidiary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First Interstate Bancorp said Monday it would
sell its Commercial Alliance Corp. subsidiary, one of the largest
U.S. providers of capital equipment financing, to a Japanese
leasing giant for $190 million.
   The sale to Tokyo-based Orix Corp., Japan's largest leasing
company, is expected to close by the end of September. Closing
conditions include approval by the Japanese Ministry of Finance,
the company said in announcing the definitive agreement.
   The sale is part of a nearly 2-year-old restructuring at First
Interstate that has included layoffs, other cost-cutting measures
and the sale of many non-core businesses as the company
concentrates on consumer and business banking.
   First Interstate, a vast banking enterprise with offices in 21
states and the District of Columbia, began the restructuring due
largely to losses at its Texas unit.
   Joseph J. Pinola, chairman and chief executive officer, has been
upbeat about company prospects in recent months after a string of
positive earnings reports, and share prices have risen.
   First Interstate said it agreed to provide some interim funding
for Commercial Alliance, a worldwide operation that has 23 offices
throughout the United States.
   As of June 30, Commercial Alliance had had total assets of $1.9
billion. Net income for the 12 months ended June 30 was $14.8
million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
