<FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-89 2229EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-JerricoMerger     08-07 0166</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jerrico Merger,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parent Of Long John Silver Chain to Merge With Investment Companies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jerrico Inc., the owner of the Long John
Silver's Seafood Shoppes chain, announced a $620 million merger
agreement Monday with a group controlled by DJS-Inverness &amp; Co. and
Castle Harlan Inc.
   The New York-based investment companies will acquire all of
Jerrico's common stock for $24.25 a share in cash, Jerrico said in
a news release. The deal is valued at about $620 million.
   The investment group will commence a tender offer through a new
corporation later this week for all outstanding Jerrico shares,
which will be subject to the condition that at least 51 percent of
Jerrico's common stock is tendered.
   The corporation already controls the Steak and Ale restaurant
chain.
   DJS-Inverness was formed in 1988 through the combination of the
DJS Group of New York and the Inverness Group of Houston.
   Castle Harlan, a merchant bank, controls Legend Group L.P., a
limited partnership formed in 1987.
</TEXT>
