<FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-89 2331EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru f0287 08-07 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0287,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Slips, Share Prices Rebound</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with late dollar, Nikkei morning close.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar slipped against the Japanese yen
Tuesday morning, while share prices rebounded slightly on the Tokyo
Stock Exchange.
   The dollar opened at 139.55 yen and moved in a range of 139.10
to 139.65 yen. It stood at 139.23 yen, down 0.55 yen from Monday's
139.78-yen close, at midday.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 19.54
points, or 0.06 percent, to close the morning session at 34,649.92.
The index had lost 111.61 points the previous day.
   The dollar's bearishness in the Tokyo market followed its slight
loss in New York overnight mainly due to profit-taking by
speculative investors, traders said.
   ``The market was relatively quiet all morning,'' said a dealer
at the Bank of Japan, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Another trader at Chemical Bank's Tokyo office, Minori Takeuchi,
said, ``In the absence of fresh market-affecting news, early
dealings in Tokyo have been very technical.''
   Traders said the dollar has been weak due to prospects that U.S.
interest rates are unlikely to decline further, judging from the
lower-than-expected U.S. jobless rate in July that indicated
moderate economic growth is continuing.
   On Friday, Washington reported that the U.S. unemployment rate
for July fell by 0.1 percentage point to 5.2 percent.
   Securities dealers said trading was light because many investors
are on summer vacation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
